<HEAD>First Lady: Trauma of Shooting Led to Astrologer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 First Lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Monday she consulted an astrologer on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s travel schedule because she was `` obsessed with his safety'' after he was shot in March 1981. It was `` a terrible trauma'' when her husband was shot, `` and you're in shock much longer than you know you're in shock,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in a CBS News interview. `` And you reach out anywhere for, for comfort.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was first reported to have consulted an astrologer on her husband's schedule in a book by former White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>. The White House later confirmed it. Interviewed during CBS' coverage of the Republican National Convention, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told anchorman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON> that some months after the attack on her husband she heard about a woman who had said she would have warned against his public appearance that day. `` And I said, ` Oh, gee, did she really?' And I was so obsessed with his safety, that anytime he went out of the house, I think my heart stopped,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` So all I would do would, would be to ask her, ` Is, is this a, would he be all right? Is it better for him to go to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Wednesday or Tuesday?'''
