<SECOND>Retired U.S. News &amp; World Report Chief Dead At 81</SECOND>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON>, a retired president, board chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; World Report, died Sunday of cardiopulmonary arrest at a nursing home in this <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> suburb. He was 81. Sweet came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1946 and joined the old <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Report </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> as its circulation manager. Two years later, when World Report merged with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, he became circulation director of the new publication. Sweet later headed the advertising and the research and promotion departments before becoming executive vice president and publisher in 1951. He was named president of the magazine in 1958 and was promoted to board chairman and chief executive officer in 1973. He stepped down as CEO in 1981 and as board chairman the following year. During his years with the magazine, it grew from a circulation of 250,000 and revenue of $ 3.4 million to a circulation of more than 2 million and advertising revenue of more than $ 70 million a year. Survivors include his wife, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>; one son, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Altos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; and one daughter, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Ternes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>.
