<HEAD>Thousands Gather at Church Where Four Claim to Hear Messages from
Mary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 8-9 bgng `To some' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
quotes from priest, add explanation. Subs 15th graf pvs `The
reported' to CORRECT that only two in Yugoslavia claim to still see
apparitions. Subs final graf to restore first reference.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Worshipers screamed and lifted their hands toward the sky as a ray of light burst through the clouds Monday evening during an outdoor Mass where thousands came expecting a miracle. Shortly after the 6 p.m. Mass began at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neumann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, throngs of pilgrims stood and applauded as many spectators pointed skyward, crying that they saw <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and calling it a miracle. `` I saw the sun pulsating a lot and saw <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> about 10 times,'' said <PERSON> Mamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Fertitta </PERSON>. `` Then I saw <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> above and the doves below.'' A dozen priests standing on a rooftop altar and 600 Eucharist ministers turned their backs to the crowd to look at the sky and wave. After minutes of silence, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Neumann </PERSON> pastor Monsignor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> began to sing `` Amazing Grace.'' People in the audience whipped out cameras to photograph the clouds and light. `` I saw baby <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> for an instant in the sky,'' said <PERSON> Koreth </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargahese </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> estimated the crowd for the service at about 12,000 people. To some in the crowd the shape they saw in the sky was the miracle they had been hoping for. Their shouts alerted others. Some then reported seeing the same apparation and others did not. `` I'm positive other people saw things and they took photographs,'' said Father <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, a Benedictine monk from <LOCATION> Pecos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` I did n't see anything, but some of the other priests on the altar did,'' <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, a deacon of the <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION> parish. Monday was the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> feast of the ascension of the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> into heaven. The crowds were drawn to the charismatic parish in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> by national attention given to three parishioners' reports that they received messages from the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> this spring, including tidings of miracles on the feast day Earlier Monday, parish members and priests laid hands on the pilgrims and said prayers for the scores of handicapped people present. Hundreds of people in wheelchairs and walkers settled on the grassy hillside beneath a 60-foot-long altar built atop the church office. `` I heard that <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>'s crown was spinning on the statue inside the church last night, so I believe anything can happen,'' said <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> as she stepped off a bus with 43 other Catholics from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Parish officials did not confirm the rumor about the crown. <PERSON> James </PERSON> said he did not know whether attendance would reach the 20,000 people he said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> told him would come. `` It does n't matter how many are here. Some beautiful spirtual things are going on.'' The reported messages at the church came after <PERSON> James </PERSON> and several parishioners returned from <LOCATION> Medugorje </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, where six youths claimed they began seeing apparitions of <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> in 1981 and two say they still see them daily. One group skeptical of the reports said the trip and the beginning of the messages was too coincidental to be believable. `` While we are certainly open to any verifiable paranormal events, so far the only amazing thing that has happened here is the fact that thousands of people would flock here from all over, against common sense, on the unverified claims of one man,'' said <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Madison </PERSON>, spokesman for West Texans to Promote Rational Thought, a group that investigates claims of paranormal behavior. The three parishioners say <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and God speak to them during Monday night recitations of the rosary. The trio write the `` messages'' in notebooks and read them aloud after the service. `` I feel her love, her joy, her sorrow and that's what I write down,'' said one of the three, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Constancion </PERSON>, a former hospital therapist who quit her job to devote more time to prayer and church work.
