<HEAD>Company Thinking Small With Furniture For Little People</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actor <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Barty </PERSON> was delighted as he settled his 3-foot-9 frame into the blue and white chair. His feet touched the ground. `` How can you put a price on the smile that came across his face?'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Sunburst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Outdoor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION>, which is beginning production on one of the first specially designed lines for dwarfs, midgets and other adults of small stature. `` To be able to sit in a chair with your feet touching the ground is something average-size people do n't even think about,'' <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON> said. `` For little people, it's an uncommon thrill.'' <PERSON> Barty </PERSON>, a consultant on the project, said the Sunburst outdoor furniture designs are among the first of any kind of furniture produced specifically for `` little people,'' as he terms anyone afflicted by the nearly 200 different forms of dwarfism. `` We are a minority that is really a minority,'' said the 63-year-old actor in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, where he is filming a movie. `` We are mostly handicapped by physical barriers we face. Clothes have to be cut down; light switches are too high.'' `` I ca n't tell you how wonderful it felt like to sit in a chair with your feet on the ground and your back in the proper place,'' added <PERSON> Barty </PERSON>, who has championed the little people's cause since the late 1950s. Sunburst, which supplies outdoor furniture to resorts and hotels around the world, began thinking small last year with a line of children's furniture for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>. Company founder and president <PERSON> R.W </PERSON>. <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON>, who had built a scaled-down bar and stool set for a dwarf couple three years ago, thought the children's furniture might be adapted for the nation's 1.5 million little people A letter was sent in March to <PERSON> Barty </PERSON> at his Foundation For Little People office in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Barty </PERSON> quickly responded and arranged a visit to the Sunburst production center in <LOCATION> Hialeah </LOCATION> shortly after the release of `` Willow,'' in which he plays a high priest `` But he immediately showed us that furniture for little people and children are very different,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON>, arranging three chairs side by side. The children's chair was smaller but in the same proportions as the adult version. The little people's model was modified with a low seat and elevated armrests to accommodate their shorter limbs and torsos. `` It was a real learning experience for us,'' <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON> said. `` You just ca n't put a little person in children's furniture. It does n't work and they are not comfortable. They have their own special dimensions.'' Sunburst, a division of <ORGANIZATION> MetalTech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, unveiled the Rainbow Collection in July at a convention in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, attended by about 600 little people. <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON> took about 80 furniture orders. Many had special requests, such as an extra narrow seat for a woman with a rare, acute form of dwarfism. The profit for Sunburst in the venture is also small, he said. `` To be candid, a big manufacturer would not touch this project,'' <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON> said. `` It's not smart business. It's not a big-volume-type deal. But this company has been fortunate, and we'd like to give something back and not just think about the dollars involved. Sunburst, which had sales of about $ 5 million last year, scored a success in 1964 with the patent of an aluminum umbrella designed to withstand harsh weather and high winds. The umbrellas are used in most fast-food franchises and many hotels worldwide, <PERSON> Buzzella </PERSON> said. `` I know they're never going to make money on making furniture for little people,'' <PERSON> Barty </PERSON> said. `` That's what makes it so special. They have gone beyond money and done something for people who have become accustomed to being ignored.''
