<SECOND>PM-LA Mayoral Race,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaked Memos Derail Councilman's Challenge To Mayor Bradley</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaked campaign strategy memos laced with coarse remarks threaten to ignite racial tensions in the early stages of a mayoral campaign that pits a Jewish city councilman against black incumbent <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>. The memos were prepared by a consulting firm associated with 39-year-old City Councilman <PERSON> Zev </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaroslavsky </PERSON>, who is seeking to become the city's first Jewish mayor and poses by many accounts the first real challenge to <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> in a decade. Both are Democrats; the race is nonpartisan. The documents by veteran strategists <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Agostino </PERSON>, whose firm is known as BAD Campaigns, berate <PERSON> Yaroslavsky </PERSON> about his grim demeanor, mock <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s intelligence, refer to environmentalists as `` tree huggers'' and slow-growth advocates as `` crazed homeowners.'' The strategists urge <PERSON> Yaroslavsky </PERSON>, who represents a chunk of the city's largely affluent and liberal west side, to skip <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> meetings and focus his energies on fund-raising efforts among Jewish contributors. `` What we do know is that Jewish wealth in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> is endless,'' said one of the memos, which were leaked anonymously. Elsewhere, the advisers wrote: `` The reason why BAD thinks you can beat <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> is: You've got 50 IQ points on him -LRB- and that's no compliment -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> and <PERSON> D'Agostino </PERSON>, after the memos' release last week, announced their `` regrets that our private, irreverent attempts at humor might have caused embarrassment or offense.'' <PERSON> Yaroslavsky </PERSON> quickly divorced himself from the consultants, saying, `` I do not agree with many of their ideas and I find many of their statements to be insulting, insensitive and not reflective of my views.'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridley-Thomas </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said the memos' contents `` come perilously close to being blatant racist remarks. `` At the absolute minimum they're highly insensitive,'' he said. He said the memos threaten to inflame black resentment over a perceived lack of Jewish support during <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s failed 1986 campaign for governor, and over tensions that emerged between Jews and blacks during <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s Democratic presidential bid earlier this year. The mayor, who at age 70 is seeking an unprecedented fifth term as mayor of the nation's second-largest city, denounced the memos as unprincipled and potentially racially divisive. `` Talking about the relative intelligence of candidates is of no consequence,'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. `` I think I've demonstrated over the years my intelligence and my ability to handle the public's problems. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> has become politically vulnerable because of his protracted tenure of 16 years and position on environmental issues. He has switched from opposition to approval of a proposed onshore drilling project near <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palisades </LOCATION>, an exclusive canyon enclave overlooking the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. Despite its name, BAD Campaigns is a highly regarded firm. `` <PERSON> D'Agostino </PERSON> and <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> are extremely well-respected as very capable and talented and winning consultants,'' said former Republican <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Bobbi </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> found his advice amusing when <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> submitted similar pointed comments during <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s unsuccessful 1969 mayoral campaign and in 1973, when he was elected the first black mayor of a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> city. `` When it's excerpted, it becomes a bit embarrassing,'' <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> said of the memos. `` We do n't mean to offend anybody. We had no intention of offending the mayor on the IQ.'' <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, summing up the controversy, said, `` I think what's happened is that the voters have been given a glimpse into what politics is really like. Political consultants in general `` tend to see themselves as the movers and shakers and the candidate as the vehicle,'' she said. `` So they often will seem somewhat arrogant and paternal to this woeful candidate.''
