<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos' Home Province Still Backs Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAOAG, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In his northern <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> stronghold, <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> remains a pervasive, respected figure more than two years after a Manila-based uprising toppled his 20-year authoritarian regime. `` I tell you that if he ran again, he would win hands down here,'' said <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Benemerito </PERSON>, mayor of the town of <LOCATION> Pagudpud </LOCATION> in the province of <LOCATION> Ilocos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Norte </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was born in 1917. `` You know, we Ilocanos are very clannish.'' In most of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> years are associated with massive corruption, economic mismanagement and oppression. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has refused to allow <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, where he fled after the February 1986 uprising that propelled her to power. But in his native province, <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> still enjoys widespread respect among his fellow Ilocanos. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> rewarded the province, which has a population of about 440,000, with roads and development projects. Ilocanos are strongly represented within the armed forces, although precise figures are not available. Rep. <PERSON> Roque </PERSON> <PERSON> Ablan </PERSON>, a pro-Marcos congressman, says allegations of massive corruption and embezzlement of up to $ 10 billion have not significantly dented support for the ousted leader. `` In spite of all the accusations and charges, we still look up to Mr. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Ablan </PERSON> said. `` We would like to see him come home, which is the right of every Filipino.'' The spirit of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> looms over this province, about 250 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Rural bus stops and walls of buildings in <LOCATION> Laoag </LOCATION>, the provincial capital, still bear graffiti such as `` No To Cory'' or `` Marcos Once More,'' his slogan in the fraud-tainted 1986 election. Most provincial and municipal officials elected in regional balloting in January are members of or have been aligned with <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, which has virtually disintegrated elsewhere in the country. In the town hall of <LOCATION> Batac </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> family ancestral home, pictures of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, hang on the walls of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> office. There is no picture of Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. `` People here still respect Mr. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Abaya </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic priest in <LOCATION> Batac </LOCATION>. `` They would like to see him come home, although not necessarily as president. They respect him for his intelligence.'' Pro-Marcos politicians insist they are no longer anxious for <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return as president but as a private citizen. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> claimed he won the 1986 election against Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> and left <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> only after having himself sworn into office. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> loyalists were linked to at least three major attempts to topple the Aquino government. `` In all our conversations with Mr. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, he always told us to cooperate with the Aquino government and join hands to fight the communists,'' <PERSON> Ablan </PERSON> said. But not every Ilocano is a dedicated <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> loyalist. Communist rebels have made strong inroads in <ORGANIZATION> Ilocos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> N