<FIRST>r p PM-CVN--OutnumberedRepublicans     08-15 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CVN--Outnumbered Republicans,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Convene In An Overwhelmingly Democratic Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At first glance, the Republicans appear to have gathered in hostile political territory, but an overwhelming Democratic registration edge masks growing Republican strength in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. New Orleans Mayor <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthelemy </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Democrat </PERSON> and a vice chairman of the national <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, leads a city where registered Democrats outnumber registered Republicans 189,741 to 34,853. Statewide, there are 2,146,867 registered voters and only about 322,000 of them _ 15 percent _ are Republicans. In the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, there are 23 Republicans among the 144 members. Republicans have been scarce in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> since Reconstruction. Populist Democrats like <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, who taxed oil companies to provide free state services, further cemented the Democrats' hold on the state. When blacks became a voting force as a result of the civil rights movement, Democrats broadened their base, despite occasional defections by white voters to states' rights candidates. But things are looking up for the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> GOP. Republicans have won five of the last eight presidential races in the state. Half of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s eight <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> House members are Republicans now. Ten years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> registration was just 79,900 and the long-standing joke was that they could hold the state convention in a telephone booth. Chinks in the Democrats' <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> fortress first were seen more than 30 years ago, when the state went for <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> in the 1956 presidential race. In later years, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s electoral votes went to Republicans <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> in 1964, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> in 1972 and <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1980 and 1984. In 1972, <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Treen </PERSON>, after three losing campaigns, became the first Republican to win a congressional seat in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> since Reconstruction. <PERSON> Treen </PERSON> later became the first Republican governor since Reconstruction when he was elected to the post in 1979. Ironically, he was helped by a law the Democrats had pushed to help themselves _ the unique `` open primary'' law. All candidates from all parties run in one election. If no candidate wins a majority, the top two finishers, regardless of party, face a runoff. The law was designed to keep Democrats from exhausting their energies and campaign funds in volatile primary battles against each other only to face a single, well-financed Republican in a general election. But, since anyone could vote _ regardless of party registration _ it allowed conservative Democrats to cross party lines and vote for Republicans. In addition to <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> gains, former Republican Rep. <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> forced Democrat <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON> to wage a tough, come-from-behind battle in 1986 to keep Democratic control of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat left vacant by the retirement of <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, a powerful Democrat and son of <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>. All is not roses for the Republicans in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, even with the open primary. For example, Democrats remain so strong that the planners for the 1988 GOP convention yanked Democratic Mayor <PERSON> Barthelemy </PERSON> off the schedule for their nationally televised opening night ceremonies so his welcoming remarks would be made during a less conspicuous morning session. After his 1986 loss to <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said he did not think a Republican could beat a Democrat in a head-to-head match. That was three years after <PERSON> Treen </PERSON> was overwhelmingly defeated when popular two-term governor <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, a Democrat, returned to politics after a four-year hiatus. And, although <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' political fortunes fell with the price of oil and the state's poor economy, it took another Democrat, <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, to drive <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> out of office in last year's election. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> came from the back of a five-man pack to beat <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Livingston </PERSON>, the Republican who had been considered a sure bet for a runoff with <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. <PERSON> Treen </PERSON> believes the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> GOP's growing strength results in part from the tenacity of Republicans like him who ran against enormous odds in the 1950s and 1960s. `` If I had the wisdom of my present age, which is 60, when I ran for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, I probably would not have run for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> back in 1962,'' he said. But he does not regret it. `` That race led to the'64 race and the'68 race ... and eventually to the race I won in 1972.''
