<TEXT>
 New Hampshire Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> is leading a Republican National Convention assault on his neighbor, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, saying the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee has displayed `` an absolute incapacity to manage.'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, a frequent critic of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor, conducted a spirited denunciation of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> record on the eve of the GOP convention. And <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, who will speak to the convention Tuesday night, added: `` I'm saving the good stuff.'' `` It takes an absolute incapacity to manage to have reached the fiscal chaos that <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> has today,'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said at a news conference Sunday following a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> governors and former governors. He was joined by a half-dozen other governors as he attacked <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' management of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> budget in the face of a severe deficit this year. He said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> failed to take steps that other governors did to head off a deficit when they saw indications of an economic slowdown. To deal with the resulting shortage, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> resorted to borrowing from the retirement fund for state employee pensions, as well as tax increases, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said. `` The fact is that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had no handle on his budget. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had no capacity to deal with a tough situation that he created on his own,'' <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had no management understanding, in a timely way, of what should have been done, and what <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has done since then in order to deal with next year's deficit is absolutely irresponsible.'' He used the word `` steal'' to describe the state's borrowing from its pension system and said the action `` ought to strike fear in the hearts of anyone who draws a Social Security check.'' At a brunch earlier, former Gov. <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> delivered a plea for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> not to forget that states need to take action to deal with problems, even while the Republicans `` put a harness on the government in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.'' `` Somebody's got to fix the schools and save the outdoors and fix the roads and clean the streets,'' he said. `` And you do n't get to be a governing conservative majority by voting ` no' in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> alone. Most of the work that's done on schools and jobs and the outdoors is done by governors.'' Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Castle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> governors, urged a close examination of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' record during his three terms as governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, saying the state had merely benefited from an economic boom throughout <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. `` There is some concern that the ` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Miracle,' which has been presented by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, may not be quite a miracle,'' <PERSON> Castle </PERSON> said, referring to the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign slogan for the state's economic health. `` ... Perhaps it's a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> mirage.'' At <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign headquarters in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Akey </PERSON> did not immediately return a reporter's call seeking comment.
