<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A restoration effort this summer is returning the stately old <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chamber to the way it looked in 1905 when fellows who carried pocket watches and used spittoons debated there. It'll cost the taxpayers $ 21 million before it's over in December, but those purple walls will be a thing of the past. They will be repainted to a peach tone, to go with the new red rug. `` These colors are all wrong,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Moe </PERSON>, who heads a subcommittee in charge of the restoration. `` The purple should not be here. We ca n't find anyone who will admit recommending it.'' It went on in the 1970s. The building's exterior also will be cleaned and repaired, and new gold leaf will be applied to the ball atop the dome.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FULLERTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> say they've found an almost foolproof way to reduce the number of raucous parties in their cities: bill the hosts for the time it takes to break up the noisy get-togethers Eleven <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> cities have approved ordinances within the past year enabling police to take such action. Under the ordinances, if police have to return after issuing a warning, the host will be billed for personnel and equipment costs. `` It's worked beyond our wildest dreams,'' <ORGANIZATION> Fullerton </ORGANIZATION> police Sgt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` Since it went into effect, I guess that there are 1,000 parties we've gone to, and I think we've gone back -LRB- a second time -RRB- 10 times,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. Hosts, however, have not been overly thrilled about paying up. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasater </PERSON> of <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Habra </PERSON> said he has no intention of paying his bill, even if it is only $ 16.44. `` I ai n't paying it,'' he said. `` They can take me to jail for $ 16.'' <PERSON> Lasater </PERSON>, who threw a party for his daughter's high school graduation in June, said he immediately broke up the party after his first warning, but some guests lingered in the street and police had to disperse them. `` The city has n't chosen what to do if people ignore the billing,'' said Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rees </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Habra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
