<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Police Turn Back Student March For Reunification</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Monday clash. Picks up 9th
graf pvs, `Fewer students ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Firing volleys of tear gas, riot police on Monday broke off a student march to the North Korean border to press for reunification. Police arrested and beat scores of protesters. About 2,500 students holding red and blue banners tried to march out of <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to go to the border truce village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>, about 30 miles away. Hundreds of riot troopers in green combat fatigues and black-visored helmets confronted students as soon as they exited the main gate. Some officers were seen beating students with riot shields and making flkying karate kicks at fleeing protesters. The students did not fight back and most were unarmed except for a few carrying clubs. Some students hurled a few stones, but the protesters only fought back with clubs and rocks when the police charged into the campus. Dozens of students seized by police huddled on the ground, clinging to each other as police hit and kicked them. Some students cried with pain and senior police officers hit some of their own troopers to try and stop the beating. The students made three atrempts to march out of the main gate. Each time, they were driven back by charging police and armored vans firing tear gas. The students marched out after a rally to call for reunification with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. They wanted to go to <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> for talks with North Korean student delegates on reuniting the divided Korean pensinsula. The government banned the march and deployed more than 20,000 riot police to stop it. On Sunday, hundreds of students at <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> and another college in central <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> battled riot police with firebombs and rocks, and furious residents demanded a halt to the protests to protect the Olympics. Fewer students appeared to be involved than in clashes on Saturday. The few thousand radicals involved in the protests have virtually no public support and clashes were confined to two or three small areas. Students tried to stage a number of demonstrations in downtown <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, but handfuls of protesters were dispersed quickly by hundreds of riot police. Police said more than 5,000 riot troops were deployed to block the protests. National Police Headquarters said hundreds of people were arrested, but it had no overall figures. Officials said 1,027 protesters were arrested in clashes Saturday and 63 troopers injured, most in clashes around <LOCATION> Yonsei </LOCATION>. Police halted and searched students entering or leaving <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday. Dozens of students were arrested and troops were seen beating and kicking some detainees. Angry residents and shopkeepers staged several counter-protests to demand that students stop violent demonstrations. Onlookers heckled student demonstrators in the city. `` No firebombs by students,'' they shouted. About 200 residents went to the main gate of <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> Sunday to demand students end the protest, but the students refused. Citizens also argued with protesters near the city's <LOCATION> Myondong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cathedral </LOCATION>, accusing them of sabotaging the Summer Olympics scheduled to begin in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Sept. 17. People told the students their protests embarrassed the nation. A column of about 1,000 people who said they belonged to the previously unknown `` Youth League for Protection of the Nation'' staged a march in central <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, chanting: `` Successful Olympics and economic development.'' Dozens of onlookers applauded. Students attacked some of the group's marchers with sticks and rocks near <ORGANIZATION> Seoul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> before being driven off by police. President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> warned Friday that violent protests were a threat to the Olympics and had to be stopped. Radical students have seized on the reunification issue to try to mobilize public support for their anti-government campaign. The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have failed to gain support because of violent tactics and open advances to the communist north. The students say they are not communists but insist the peninsula be reunited immediately, with political differences to be worked out later. Most South Koreans fear the north is determined to conquer them. The radical students also demand removal of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The Korean peninsula has been divided since 1945 at the end of World War II. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the south in 1950 to start the Korean War.
