arty </ORGANIZATION> right now is limited,'' said <PERSON> Rondeno </PERSON>. `` Unfortunately, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has been the party of ` keep it small and keep it all'. Blacks in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> were totally excluded from this convention.'' Most attending Sunday night's dinner and reception, however, preferred to stress the potential gain for both minorities and Republicans in a stronger relationship. But they made it clear that the party's establishment must extend a hand in welcome. `` That's what the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has to do, open up its doors,'' said <PERSON> Californian </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` The party has to have more blacks at all levels, at all echelons.'' `` This is designed to let the convention know there are minorities who do support the ticket,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, businessman who organized the group. King shrugged off questions about the number of blacks and other minorities at the convention. `` I think that's basically the way things are,'' he said. `` There are not a lot of black Republicans.''
