<HEAD>Artist Who Went From Graffiti to Museums</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Basquiat </PERSON>, a one-time graffiti artist whose paintings are displayed in the Museum of Modern Art and have sold for tens of thousands of dollars, has died at age 27. The Brooklyn-born <PERSON> Basquiat </PERSON> died Friday of either a heart attack or a drug overdose, according to his agent, <PERSON> Vrej </PERSON> <PERSON> Baghoomian </PERSON>. Basquiat's paintings were exhibited in galleries in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, and sold for $ 25,000 to $ 50,000, <PERSON> Baghoomian </PERSON> said. His paintings, featuring angular figures, symbols and words, are included in the collections of the Museum of Modern Art and the <ORGANIZATION> Whitney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Basquiat </PERSON> had no formal training and started his career scrawling graffiti on buildings with a friend, <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>. The two signed their work <PERSON> Samo </PERSON>, followed by a copyright symbol. He was a close friend of <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s and the two collaborated on a series of works in 1985 that featured cartoon characters and corporate logos. Basquiat is survived by his father, <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON>, and his mother, <PERSON> Matilde </PERSON>, and two sisters.
