<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who died of cancer two decades after his father ordered use of Agent Orange in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, once swam through water doused with the defoliant to collect weapons from <ORGANIZATION> Viet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cong </ORGANIZATION> boats. He won over his crew, but that swim may have marked the beginning of his last battle, with the cancer that ended his life Saturday at age 42. Retired Adm. <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the American naval commander in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> who ordered the spraying of the defoliant then thought to be harmless, said his son's death will only push him to work harder to force the government to compensate veterans who suffered from Agent Orange's effects. `` There are still many hundreds of veterans who do need help,'' <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> said the day his son died. `` I believe very strongly now that the evidence is clear that the Agent Orange is responsible for the problems many veterans are having.'' His son was diagnosed in 1983 as having non-Hodgkins lymphoma. Two years later, doctors found he had lymphoma <PERSON> Hodgkins </PERSON> disease. His son, <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON>, suffers from a congenital dysfunction that confuses his physical senses. The Zumwalts chronicled their battle with cancer in 1986 with the book, `` My Father, My Son,'' which they wrote with author <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pekkanen </PERSON>. The book was made into a television movie in May. <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> said his son was strong until the end, even joking and teasing with relatives during Friday evening. He died in his sleep Saturday morning. `` I do not second guess the decisions Dad made in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, nor do I doubt for a minute that the savi