<HEAD>Hirohito Says Thought Of War Dead Still Pains Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> said today at a ceremony marking the 43rd anniversary of the end of World War II that `` it still hurts my heart'' to think of those who died in battle and their families. He also praised <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s development and expansion since the end of the war. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, 87, the only surviving leader of the major participating countries in the war, walked slowly at the public hall outside the Imperial Palace in central <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The moment of silence traditionally held at noon sharp was delayed briefly while he shuffled to the microphone. However, he walked without assistance and spoke in a firm voice. `` Today, on the day to honor the war dead and pray for peace, I think of those who died in battle in the last war and their bereaved families, and it still hurts my heart,'' he said. `` Time flies fast, and in the 43 years since the end of the war, the country has developed due to people's efforts,'' he said. The emperor underwent surgery last year so doctors could perform a bypass around a growth in his pancreas. Since then, his public appearances have been limited. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, who also attended the ceremony, said it is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s duty to help maintain peace and not let war recur. The ceremony, held on the 43rd anniversary of the day <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> surrendered, was attended by about 7,000 people, including members of the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. Meanwhile, thousands of Japanese went to the <LOCATION> Yasukuni </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shrine </LOCATION>, dedicated to the Japanese war dead. Among them were many politicians and several members of the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. However, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> decided not to go, following a policy set by his predecessor, <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>. Among the 2.4 million Japanese war dea