<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-tech toilet seat that lowers automatically and a speaking smoke detector that gives warnings in English or Spanish are among the 250,000 products being displayed at the National Hardware Show. With a push of the button, the seat can automatically move up or down. It also can remove odors with its fanning mechanism and charcoal filter, adjust its temperature to suit any posterior and can kill germs with an ultraviolet light. While the seat does eliminate some age-old conflicts between men and women, there is a catch. It retails for $ 350. `` The price is too high,'' acknowledged <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiu </PERSON>, who developed the device and is director of <ORGANIZATION> Eletto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` Most people wo n't pay $ 350 for what this can do. At that price, I doubt if I'd buy it myself.'' The four-day show, which began Sunday, is the biggest in its 43-year history and the country's largest trade show, said manager <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolson </PERSON>. About 70,000 retailers are expected to attend. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hardware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schaumburg </ORGANIZATION>, said do-it-yourselfers are fueling the industry. They spent $ 52 billion last year at hardware, home center and building supply outlets, and the market is expected to grow by 12 percent annually, to total $ 100 billion by 1990, he said. `` Do-it-yourself people are moving the home improvement industry outdoors,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Dolson </PERSON>. `` It's a recreational thing for the yuppie generation and we see tremendous growth in this area.'' 