<HEAD>Government Abolishes State Tourism Organization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government announced today it will abolish the state tourism agency and said major hotels, restaurants and other facilities will be sold or leased to the private sector. The Revolution Command Council, which passed the decree Aug. 2, said state-run assets to be privatized included seven hotels in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, as well as properties in the war-battered southern port city of <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION> and the northern city of <LOCATION> Mosul </LOCATION>. Hotels not sold will be leased for 25 years to private companies, the council said. The <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION> Sheraton Hotel was damaged by shell and rocket fire during a Iranian offensive in early 1987, when some of the heaviest fighting in the 8-year-old <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war took place. The state-owned facilities also include a tourist complex in <LOCATION> Habaniya </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, and several modern resorts in the northern mountains, the scene of heavy fighting in the war. The managers of the hotels said they did not know if the facilities will be sold to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s private sector or to their parent companies. Officials said the hotels are to be run by their parent chains in accordance with an agreement signed with the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government. Tourism in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which is rich in archaeological sites, has diminished as a result of the conflict, but no statistics were available. The move to sell the facilities is part of President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s drive to stimulate the economy. The announcement came as Iranian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> leaders prepared to meet in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Aug. 25 for peace talks under a United Nations-mediated cease-fire.
