<TEXT>
 Showers and thunderstorms fell on much of the nation today after damaging winds whipped through southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. The storms extended this morning from western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> across northern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, southern <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, over <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, east, central <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, northeastern <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and central <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. A tornado Sunday ripped the roof from a gas station and uprooted trees in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and rough weather from a dying tropical depression pounded much of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. No injuries were reported. On Sunday evening, thunderstorm winds extended from east, central <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> across <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Winds reached 71 mph at <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and damaged trees and power lines near <LOCATION> Hamlin </LOCATION>, N.Y. In <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, winds gusted to near 60 mph across northern <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Severe thunderstorms in the state's southern <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> unleashed a tornado that leveled two barns, killed 15 cows and knocked out electricity to thousands, including state police. There were no injuries. This morning, thunderstorm gusts reached 55 mph over northern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, 60 mph near <LOCATION> Lagrange </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, and near 60 mph at <LOCATION> Tucson 