<HEAD>`French Connection' Cop Here to Make Film on Missing Heroin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former detective who was the basis for <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Hackman </PERSON>'s character in `` The French Connection'' says he's making a sequel on how heroin seized in the bust was later stolen from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> police vaults. The tale will unfold in a two-hour, $ 8 million movie <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> plans to start filming in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> in the fall, he said. <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>'s role in helping crack the French Connection heroin trafficking scheme was portrayed in the 1971 Academy Award-winning movie, in which <PERSON> Hackman </PERSON> played a character named <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> `` Popeye'' <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>. Now, <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> wants to tell the rest of the story _ how 112 pounds of heroin he and his partner recovered in 1962 were discovered missing a decade later from the police property clerk's office and ended up on the streets of southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` It was what I have to term as the perfect crime,'' <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said. `` Nobody was watching the store.'' He said the film, `` Internal Affair,'' will show how criminals got on the police force and over several years smuggled heroin out of <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> vaults, replacing it with worthless powder. <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> has formed a movie company, <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to produce `` Internal Affair,'' which he bills as being more intriguing than `` The French Connection.'' The stars have not been selected, but <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said they must have a drug-free background. The French Connection arrests capped an investigation filled with tedious surveillance and routine police work. It was the highlight of <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>'s 20-year police career. After the arrests, <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> was demoted and suspended for failing to catalog drugs seized as evidence. He retired in 1971 to make movies. <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>, 58, has spent the past 15 years as a character actor in TV and movie police stories such as `` Badge 373,'' `` Police Story,'' `` Prime Cut'' and `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Forrester </PERSON>.''
