<HEAD>Pilgrims Come to Church for Spiritual, Physical Healing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with service this morning, Picks
up 3rd graf, `On Sunday ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Roman Catholic pilgrims prayed today at a church here in preparation for a service tonight that many expect to bring miracles of healing. Officials estimate more than 20,000 people have journeyed from across the country to worship at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neumann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. About 5,000 people attended the first of five rosary services this morning. Hundreds camped out overnight on a grassy hillside outside the church, many bringing pillows, coolers and beach umbrellas. The temperature was expected to hit near 100 degrees today. On Sunday night, a Mass and rosary service was moved outdoors to accommodate about 2,500 people. Worshipers crowded onto the grassy slope beneath a huge altar built atop the church office for the weekend of worship and prayer. Rosary services at St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Neumann </PERSON>, a church built underground, became the focus of nationwide attention after three parishioners claimed to have received messages from the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> during weekly rosaries. The three, <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Slate </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Constancio </PERSON> and <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Werner </PERSON>, said that <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> told them to expect a miracle on today's Feast of the Assumption, the day Catholics celebrate the ascension of <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> into heaven. Mrs. <PERSON> Constancio </PERSON>, a former hospital therapist, said she and her husband quit their jobs to spend more time praying. While many handicapped people have come to the church hoping for physical healing, others said they seek spiritual renewal. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, his wife, niece and 11-year-old son drove from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, and attended Sunday's Mass. `` My son has been sick a long time,'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said. `` Last year I had to carry him in my arms. Now he can walk, but he's still sick.'' `` Maybe my son can get better,'' he said. <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> said she came to strengthen her faith. `` Like they said in church, that so many people would come here to pray together is a miracle,'' she said. `` It really does n't matter what happens.'' The throng of worshipers Sunday sparked concern from officials about crowd control for the evening service. Parking lots surrounding the church were full with the morning Mass crowd, which police estimated at about 1,300. `` I've seen people leave their car in the middle of traffic if they're late for a -LRB- football -RRB- kickoff,'' said police Col. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Huffman </PERSON>. `` You can just imagine what would happen if they're late for a miracle.''
