<HEAD>First Shark Patrols In Six Years Off Stinson Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STINSON BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first shark patrols in six years continue off <LOCATION> Stinson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> after a great white shark was seen eating a seal. Sharks may be entering the area to feed on sick or dead sea lions and seals, which have been stricken in an epidemic of a kidney disease, said Dr. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Deiter </PERSON>, a veterinarian with <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION>, which monitors marine mammal life. Last week a surfer survived a shark attack near <LOCATION> Eureka </LOCATION>, about 300 miles north of <LOCATION> Stinson </LOCATION>, a popular beach just north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Lifegaurds are cruising the area once or twice a day for signs of sharks, said lifeguard <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>. No sharks have been spotted, he said. The patrols began Wednesday after a fisherman reported seeing a shark more than 13 feet long feeding about 300 yards off shore, <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said. The beach will remain open unless a shark is spotted closer in, he said. No one has ever been attacked by a shark at <LOCATION> Stinson </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said.
