<HEAD>Early Arrivals Promised Cool Reception At Superdome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Republicans, whose only task this week is to take a foregone conclusion to a foot-stomping anti-climax, found it necessary today to hold a morning session to start things off. This is what they meant by `` Morning in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>''? There even were delegates in the cavernous Superdome when the opening gavel fell at 10 a.m., attracted possibly by the routine business at hand but more likely because the Superdome is the coolest place in town. The weather in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> is such that flies have been known to faint from the heat. Did the morning session really count since <PERSON> Dan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> were not peering down from their anchor booths? The program, to be charitable, seemed to have come out of files marked `` Not Ready for Prime Time,'' or, `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, Is n't It Wonderful?'' The schedule was drawn to pay homage to Japanese-Americans, Hispanic-Americans, College Americans, Black Americans, Teen-age Americans Female Americans, Jewish-Americans and Americans Abroad. There also was a salute to youth. All this in barely two hours along with the call to order, two ROTC color guards, the national anthem, the invocation and the pledge of allegiance led by Soviet expatriate comic <PERSON> Yakov </PERSON> <PERSON> Smirnoff </PERSON>. He was introduced by party chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, as a man who came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> seeking freedom and `` like so many Americans has given more than he received _ he's given us the gift of laughter.'' <PERSON> Smirnoff </PERSON> did his stint and ended with his trademark, `` What a Country!'' The best-known of the speakers were <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON>, the former secretary of state who made it almost to the first primary before dropping out of the presidential race, and former Gov. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, who pocketed two delegates in the first primary and then gave up. For their efforts, the two men were penciled in for 10:40 a.m. to 11 a.m., which is about as far out of the spotlight as you can get at a political convention. <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the outspoken daughter of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> stalwart, did n't fare much better: she had an early starting time, when she could be as blunt as she likes without offending too many. This was all a warm-up for the big finale at high noon: speeches by candidates for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. A far piece from prime time? Yes. But you can bet that their campaign commercials will take full advantage of those clips of glory. Without showing the clock, of course.
