<SECOND>PM-Dukakis-Executive Privilege,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>State High Court Nixes `Executive Privilege' On Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> may not invoke `` executive privilege'' to keep documents from the public, the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The unanimous decision came in the case of two homosexual men who are challenging the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration's decision to remove two young boys from foster care in their <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> home, but it could affect other issues. The Democratic presidential nominee's administration has cited `` executive privilege'' in a number of areas to avoid having to disclose internal memos and other sensitive papers. Opponents of plans to put a new prison in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION> are seeking to force disclosure of documents showing how the site was chosen. `` There is no such privilege in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>,'' the court said in an opinion written by Chief Justice <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hennessey </PERSON>. The justices said they found no justification in the state constitution or state law for withholding government documents. They said the creation of laws, rights or privileges was a policy issue best left to the Legislature. `` Had the framers of our government's structure intended to recognize in our constitution an executive privilege, it is reasonable to expect that they would expressly have created one,'' they said. `` It's a victory for accountability and open government,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON>, attorney for <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Babets </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean </PERSON>. `` The public now has a right to know how its government comes to its decisions. That is a good thing in a democracy.'' Spokesmen for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> were traveling with him to central <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and were not immediately available for comment. The case began in 1985, when the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration removed two youngsters _ then aged 3 -LCB- and 22 months _ from <LOCATION> Babets </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Jean </PERSON>. After a study, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> promulgated rules for placing foster children that gave lowest priority to homosexual individuals who lacked experience as parents and gave first priority to married couples with children. Babets and <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> Suffolk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in January 1986 challenging the legality of the rules. The suit named <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, Human Services Secretary <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> DSS </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Matava </PERSON> as defendants, although <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was later dropped as a named defendant. Babets and <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> argued that the policy discriminated and violated their constitutional rights to equal protection, free association and privacy. During the trial, lawyers for Babets and <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> asked Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> to order the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration to divulge certain documents relating to the policy-making process. After hearings and an inspection of the documents <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> ordered the government to surrender them. But <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> stayed his order and referred the constitutional questions to the appellate courts. Today's ruling specifically affirms <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>'s order, apparently forcing the state to release the requested documents.
