<HEAD>Police Stop Students from Marching to Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SEL2,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police used tear gas and beatings Monday to disperse thousands of radical students trying to march to the border for unification talks with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. At least 1,300 were arrested. President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> told the nation his government will not tolerate violent campus protest. He said unchecked student activism would endanger the Olympic Games, which open Sept. 17 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Officers were seen taking away hundreds of protesters who tried to march from <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to the border truce village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>, 35 miles north of the capital, for talks with North Korean student leaders. Witnesses saw dozens of protesters and policmen injured but no injury statistics were available. Authorities said they arrested 1,300 students but released many after warnings. Riot police fired tear gas at <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in western <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and charged into a crowd of students. They kicked protesters, beat them and dragged about 200 away. In a speech marking the 43rd anniversary of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s independence from Japanese colonial rule, <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said: `` We can not any longer tolerate activities which destroy free democracy, our way of life,'' He said the Olympics will bring East and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> together, and `` peoples around the world are praying for the success of the Games. Therefore, the people and the government will not forgive anyone who spoils the festival through mob action or the throwing of firebombs, no matter for what plausible cause.'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> delivered a similar warning Friday, accusing radical students and dissidents of siding with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and trying to overthrow the government. In the speech Monday, he also proposed a summit with President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to discuss the future of the peninsula, which was divided at the end of World War II. Similar proposals in the past have led nowhere, but the two Koreas are considering parliamentary talks on easing tension. A few hours after the speech, thousands of radical students rallied at <LOCATION> Yonsei </LOCATION> and tried to march into the streets on their way to the border. Troopers in green combat fatigues and black-visored helmets fired tear gas and charged the protesters, who shouted `` Unite the fatherland!'' and `` Yankee go home!'' Students who did not resist huddled in groups on the ground, clinging to each other as policemen beat them with fists and even riot shields. Senior officers hit and slapped their own men in an attempt to stop the beatings. One commander slashed at troopers with a riding crop. Many students apparently decided to let themselves be arrested, a change from their normal tactic of violent resistance. About 100 members of the `` unification vanguard'' tied themselves together so police would have to arrest them as a group. Among those detained were 12 leaders who were to have represented <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> at the talks Monday in <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>. Police blocked a similar march to <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> on June 10. About 3,000 radical students tried to march Monday, a much smaller number than in June, and there was virtually no evidence of public support. The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have seized on national unification in their campaign against the government. South Korean authorities declared Monday's march illegal and deployed 25,000 riot police in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to stop it. They insist that all dialogue with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> be conducted through government channels. When their march from <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> was blocked Monday, students regrouped on campus and surged out with rocks and firebombs to do battle for an hour with about 7,000 riot police. Volleys of tear gas were fired from armored police vans. About 600 protesters were arrested downtown and in other parts of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. In one confrontation in the heart of the capital, 700 students lay down on the pavement with their hands interlocked as police charged, and 200 were taken away. Student leaders told a rally at <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> they would not stop trying to oust the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> government and reunite <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Dozens of students cut their fingers with razors and wrote four Korean letters meaning `` national unification'' in blood. They denounced the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, saying <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> supports military rule in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and demanded withdrawal of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based here under a mutual defense treaty.
</TEXT>
