<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republicans opened their 34th national convention today with an unusual morning session as nominee-in-waiting <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> revealed from afar he has narrowed his list of potential running mates. The first order of business was an attack on Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a champion of `` the failed liberal policies of yesterday.'' `` What a country,'' exclaimed comedian <PERSON> Yakov </PERSON> <PERSON> Smirnoff </PERSON> after reciting the pledge of allegiance to a surprisingly large mid-morning gathering of delegates in the cavernous <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Superdome. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> remained in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> prepared a prime-time, farewell address to Republicans who twice launched him to landslide victories. `` I think the president will be very personal and the crowd reaction may be emotional,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Duberstein </PERSON>, the White House chief of staff. `` It's going to be a grand salute to the president.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remarks also were intended to arouse political passions for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, his loyal lieutenant. With <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> trailing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in most national polls, the attacks on Democrats began early with speeches by former Secretary of State <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> and former <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>, two of the five men <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> defeated en route to Wednesday night's nomination. The vice president spent his morning in a round of television interview shows, fending off questions about his running mate. `` I think my choice will be widely accepted when I decide on who that choice is,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` I've not decided,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Asked if he were leaning tow