<HEAD>Polish Primate Ignores Politics, Blasts Abortion, Pornography</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CZESTOCHOWA, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cardinal <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> on Monday condemned abortion, pornography and sexual promiscuity in a speech that ignored the nation's pressing social and economic problems. The primate's address to 150,000 pilgrims who had gathered at the <PERSON> Jasna </PERSON> <PERSON> Gora </PERSON> monastery outside <LOCATION> Czestochowa </LOCATION> marked a significant departure from sermons in recent years that have taken <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s communist leadership to task on a variety of issues The sermon came three days after <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> met with Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> to discuss ways to speed up economic and political reforms. <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> made no reference to the banned trade union Solidarity, which this month marks the eighth anniversary of the strikes that launched the outlawed federation, but scores of red-and-white Solidarity banners covered the iron gates below the monastery. A white flag with `` Solidarity'' lettered across it in red was raised by <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> activist <PERSON> Seweryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaworski </PERSON>. The homemade banner flew in full view of church dignitaries seated on a temporary outdoor platform and could be seen by the pilgrims massed in a field below. Throngs of Polish pilgrims from across the nation come together for the feast day of <LOCATION> Our </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lady </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Czestochowa </LOCATION>, regarded as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s patron saint They huddled under umbrellas for protection from the heat, but dozens fainted. The 14th century monastery is the home of the <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> icon, an age-darkened painting of the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> dating to the 8th or 9th century which some believers credit with miraculous powers. It is <L