<HEAD>China to Link Wage Raises With Price Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> soon will give its workers a large raise and link further pay increases to its inflation rate to stave off growing unrest in its cities, sources said Monday. The move marks a step back from ambitious price reforms undertaken in the last few years. But the plan still should be considered a victory for liberal-minded reformers such as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> sources said. The sources said Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, Vice Premier <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilin </PERSON> and other conservatives have called for a freeze on reforms which are slowly opening the economy to market forces. Both sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, recently attended meetings of top government officials in the resort town of <LOCATION> Bedaihe </LOCATION>. The sources said the new plan to link pay with price rises would be announced in about a month. `` It will allow the reforms to continue and that is the critical point,'' said one source. He estimated that the average worker's annual salary of $ 246 would go up at least 8 percent. The other said urban workers could be getting a 28 percent raise. If prices rise, they said, the workers would be given further wage increases. The sources said the pay increases would replace subsidies of about $ 2.70 a month that the government has been giving urban workers to offset inflation, the highest in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 39-year history as a communist nation. Prices in June were 19 percent higher than they were in June 1987, according to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. The inflation has hit urban workers the hardest. Peasants, who make up 75 percent of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 1.07 billion people, generally have missed some price increases because they produce their own food. Inflation has been rising in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> because the government has pushed far-reaching economic reforms aimed at ending state controls over prices and allowing the value of goods to be controlled by the market. In May, the government raised the state-set prices of vegetables, pork, sugar and eggs by about 60 percent. In late July, it increased the price of brand-name cigarettes and spirits by as much as 790 percent. The elimination of government-fixed prices has caused the cost of some goods to soar as the economy fails to keep up with rising consumer demand. In addition, interest rates in Chinese banks are much lower than the inflation rate, so consumers want to spend now before their money loses too much value. The Chinese sources said that under the plan banks will also raise their interest rates to encourage saving. The Economic Daily ran a front-page editorial Monday calling for such a move. In May, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials as saying riots and other signs of social turmoil were on the increase in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The sources said that in addition to placating workers, the goverment was raising salaries to increase worker productivity. `` We ca n't continue with the reforms if the economy is n't growing,'' said one source The Chinese sources, interviewed separately, described themselves as members of <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s liberal camp.
