<HEAD>Lefebvre Followers, Church Loyalists March in Dueling Processions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Roman Catholics loyal to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and followers of rebel archbishop <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> organized competing processions Monday, each attracting about 5,000 faithful to renew <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s 350-year-old vow of consecration to the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> Carrying statues and banners of the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON>, and chanting `` Hail Marys'' _ the loyalist group in French, the traditionalists in Latin _ the two sets of marchers added color to downtown streets on the Assumption Day holiday, one of the quietest days of the year in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Parisians and tourists at sidewalk cafes turned to watch the processions and puffs of incense. This was the third year of dueling processions on Aug. 15, but the competition was sharpened this year by the recent schism and excommunication of <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> for consecrating bishops without permission from Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II. It also drew added attention because Monday was the 350th anniversary of King <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XIII </PERSON>'s vow of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s loyalty to the Virgin. It is celebrated on Assumption Day, which marks the day <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> was received into heaven. Cardinal <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON>, the archbishop of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, led the official ceremony at Notre Dame Cathedral. Across the <LOCATION> Seine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in the Latin Quarter, the traditionalist procession was led by Monsignor <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Tissier </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallerais </PERSON>, one of the four bishops <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> consecrated in a ceremony June 30 at Econe, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lefrebvre </PERSON> was excommunicated for going through with the consecrations without papal permission, creating the church's first schism in more than a century. `` Those who remain faithful to Monsignor <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> will stay in the path of grace,'' <PERSON> Tissier </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallerais </PERSON> said before the procession left the church of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nicolas </LOCATION> du Chardonnet. `` Those who do nor remain faithful will lose this grace.'' The 17th century church, in the ancient Latin Quarter a few short blocks from <LOCATION> Notre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dame </LOCATION>, has been occupied since 1977 by traditionalist worshipers and priests who follow <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> in rejecting such church reforms as Mass said in modern languages instead of Latin. <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON> has taken steps recently to try to appeal to the traditionalists, including establishing the Assumption Day procession three years ago, following their example. He also said Mass in Latin at Notre Dame, and said the traditional Latin Mass would be used in three <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> churches each Sunday. `` It's an effort to co-opt people,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Baptiste </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaumeil </PERSON>, one of the marchers in the traditionalist procession. `` It shows a hypocrisy. The French bishops have always been against Monsignor <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> and tried to make sure the negotiations with <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> would fail.'' At the halfway point of their procession, at the ruins of the Roman arena of <LOCATION> Lutece </LOCATION>, there was a caged lion, which organizers said was intended to evoke the martyrdom of early Christians and symbolize the plight of <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>'s followers. Police estimated the traditionalist procession at about 5,000 people. Roughly the same number were gathered at the same time in late-afternoon sunshine in the square in front of Notre Dame Cathedral. Huge banners decorated the famous facade, including one multicolored representation of the Virgin holding the Christ child that was hung between the Western towers. Church officials said it reproduced a tapestry said to have hung in <LOCATION> Notre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dame </LOCATION> in 1638, when King Louis XIII dedicated the nation to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>. Another banner reproduced the king's words: `` We believed ourselves obliged to consecrate our person and our state to the grandeur of God.'' The processions also were linked to ceremonies worldwide marking the end of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s Marian Year, a period designated by the pope for special devotion to the mother of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>.
