<HEAD>One Of Few Black Female Federal Judges Returns To Private Practice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge stepped down from the bench Monday to return to private legal practice, leaving fewer than a dozen black women among the nation's federal trial judges. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said she considered that statistic when deciding to leave the bench after nine years. `` One of the most pressing concerns I have is my race and my sex, because I know I have brought to the bench a different perspective,'' she said. `` The federal judiciary is an institution, and an institution should reflect society.'' However, she said: `` I think I've done all I can do here. For me, it's time to move on.'' A desire to return to private practice, rather than philosophical considerations, prompted her to leave the bench. `` I'm not so much leaving, but resuming what I did the years before I came here,'' Mrs. <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said. `` I want to practice quality law.'' But she also cited overloaded dockets and lack of support services as reasons for returning to private practice. She said budget cutbacks had left each federal judge in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> struggling to handle more than 1,000 cases without enough employeees or adequate computer systems to handle the work. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, now the Democrats' vice presidential nominee, recommended Mrs. <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> for a federal judgeship when she was a lawyer handling employment discrimination cases. `` I feel very, very loyal to Senator <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>,'' she said. `` For him to appoint me when I had a reputation for suing on behalf of minorities _ that took courage.'' Mrs. <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> was sworn in May 31, 1979, whens she was 37, and became the first black and the third woman to assume a federal judgeship in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Her race came into play in several of her cases. The grand dragon of the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 asked her to step aside in a lawsuit brought by Vietnamese shrimpers who claimed they were being harassed by <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> members. Mrs. <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> refused the request, pointing out that the grand dragon had never heard her express a personal opinion about the Klan. Her race became an issue again when she presided over a dispute about attorneys' fees in a package of voting rights lawsuits brought against the city of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. The suits eventually led to changes in the way the City Council is elected. The city asked her to step down from the case in 1984, saying that as a black she was a plaintiff in the class-action suits filed on behalf of Hispanic and black voters. Mrs. <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> refused to bow out and her decision was upheld by the 5th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. `` If the 5th Circuit had not affirmed, I expect I would have left the bench then; that's how important it was,'' she said. `` A decision not to affirm would have rendered me a second-class citizen.''
