<HEAD>Ad Agency Loses State's Anti-Smoking Account Over Tobacco Ties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State health officials have canceled a $ 1.7 million contract with an ad agency to produce youth-oriented, no-smoking commercials because the agency merged with another which has a tobacco company account. The incident `` shows how long the tentacles of the tobacco industry are,'' said <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Harty </PERSON>, manager of the state <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s section on nonsmoking and health. The Campbell-Mithun agency, based in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, recently merged with New York-based <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Esty </ORGANIZATION>, which has a $ 35 million account with <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Williamson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Campbell-Mithun, which had a two-year contract with the state, developed and produced television and radio spots that have been broadcast regularly around the state since January One shows students falling over, domino-fashion, from the bad breath of a teen-age girl smoker. Another highlights the smelly odor left in smokers' clothes. The campaign, rather than focusing on long-term health risks of smoking, emphasized the lowered personal attractiveness and social isolation of the smoker. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> recently began airing animated public service ads with a similar tone, characterizing smokers as `` buttheads'' and pariahs. <PERSON> Harty </PERSON> said Friday that Campbell-Mithun would be replaced by the Martin-Williams agency of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> for at least two years. The contract with <PERSON> Campbell-Mithun </PERSON> had just been renewed when its merger with <ORGANIZATION> Esty </ORGANIZATION> was announced last month, she added. The Campbell-Mithun advertisements have been `` very effective,'' <PERSON> Harty </PERSON> said, based on measurements of audience reach and recall. <PERSON> Campbell-Mithun </PERSON> made deft use of the state's limited media-buying budget, obtaining a significant number of free spots along with those it bought, she said. <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for what now is <ORGANIZATION> Campbell-Mithun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Esty </ORGANIZATION>, said the move `` was an extremely difficult decision to reach, but it was an amicable one. We remain very, very proud of the work we did.'' Esty and the former Campbell-Mithun agencies are owned by the New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DFS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustafson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Williams </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, said the agency's projections indicate very little likelihood of landing a tobacco-linked `` Even if it should happen, we've made a commitment to -LRB- the Health Department's -RRB- section on nonsmoking,'' she said. `` We'd ask -LRB- the prospective client -RRB- to understand, but it they did n't we'd probably not pitch for their business.
