<FIRST>u p AM-CVN--EndOfAnEra Bjt   08-15 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CVN--End Of An Era, Bjt,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan a Hard Act to Follow, Really Loves His Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No one can say that we'll never see the likes of him again, but <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will be a hard act for any president to follow. The man actually enjoys the job. Other presidents pursued the office with equal ardor, but none has savored it the way <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> does. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> used to refer to the White House as `` that great white prison,'' yet he had the luxury in those safer times of taking a walk around the block. By contrast, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is swaddled in a germ-free cocoon and has n't seemed to mind. If he were to write a book, you can bet it wo n't be about the splendid misery of it all. That aura of comfort in the job invited a comment from delegate <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, that you hear often around the Republican National Convention: `` I do n't think there's anybody here who would n't like to have <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on the ticket again.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> _ and, for that matter, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ eat your heart out. Everything about <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> shows his pleasure with the best role of his actor's life. It's in his body language. He bounds onstage for speeches; he looks interested in the other guy's speech; he laughs at every punch line. His wave to crowds is never forced. Amiability is his strong suit. He has turned his age to advantage with endless variations of the same one-liner. `` I always feel at home here in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> because, you know, I'm the fellow that talked <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> into buying it,'' he said at a rally welcoming him to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> on Sunday. It got a laugh; it always does. Where other presidents were renowned for their inability to make small talk _ <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> comes to mind _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is the kind of man you'd like at your dinner party. He is a natural quipster and never more so than on the day he was shot. As he was wheeled into the operating room, he told <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, `` Honey, I forgot to duck.'' To his doctors: `` Please tell me you're all Republicans.'' and, en route to the recovery room, `` All in all, I'd rather be in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>.'' Politics aside, Americans like a man like that. He is the movie cowboy blowing the smoke away from his gun barrel, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> striding across the shot-up deck of his destroyer, <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> finding humor in the serious business of politics. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was a real war hero, but he's derided as the wimp. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s the tough guy who spent his war years making movies for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> developed a rapport with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people by extolling optimism in a dark time. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has taken pages out of FDR's book, ridiculing the malaise that <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> talked about. `` A New Beginning,'' was his campaign slogan in 1980. `` It's Morning in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' was the refrain in 1984. Who else could get away with the things <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> He and his wife speak freely of family values when their own family is torn. His reputation is that of a religious man, yet he seldom goes to church. He is caught red-handed with faulty facts, misstatements, admission of ignorance of his administration's doings and he walks away with head held high. It is, as Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said, a Teflon presidency where nothing sticks. Far from being a drawback, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s actor background has helped him mold public opinion. No matter what he says, it sounds good when he says it. Television is his medium. He handles it better than anyone since <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. Used to taking orders from directors in his earlier career, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has surrounded himself with aides to whom he delegates much authority. That enables him to be what he said he would be, a 9-to-5 executive who does not take work home. He came in to the White House with solidly rooted ideas and it has been both an attribute and a flaw that he sticks with them no matter what. His off-the-cuff public statements often draw on the 3-by-5 cards he used during his political infancy in the 1960s and even before when he honed his conservative views as a company spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is the 40th American president, the first actor, the first divorced man, and the oldest ever. His administration was tainted by scandal, by the Iran-Contra affair, by budget deficits, by curtailment of programs. None of that necessarily will be stressed by history. What will be remembered is <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
