<HEAD>Second Fire In Three Days at Landmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire broke out Monday on the 51st floor of the Empire State Building, forcing dozens of office workers to evacuate the 102-story tower, and officials said the second blaze there in three days was suspicious. The blaze, which began in a batch of carpets discarded in a stairwell, produced heavy smoke but caused only minor damage to the landmark skyscraper. Firefighters doused the fire about a half hour after it began. Authorities declined to say why the fire was declared suspicious, but Fire Commissioner <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> said the investigation would include why 10 rolled-up carpets were stashed in the stairwell. Chief <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Manson </PERSON>, the deputy borough commander who commanded fire forces at the scene in last Friday's fire as well as the one Monday, said he had found nothing to link the two blazes, department spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> said. One woman in the building fell but declined medical treatment, and a second was removed to <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> with possible cardiac arrest. One firefighter was sent to <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION> for treatment of smoke inhalation and heat exhaustion. The temperature was about 94 and rising at the time of the fire, which was reported at 11:34 a.m. and extinguished at 12:12 p.m.. An off-duty firefighter visiting his brother discovered the fire and helped to put it out, <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> said Between 50 to 100 tenants on the five floors of the tower's midsection, floors 51 through 56, were evacuated because of the smoke, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON>, a management spokesman for the building The Fire Department initially reported that the fire started in an electrical conduit in a 50th floor stairwell; later, the department attributed the cause to the burning carpets. On Friday, a fire broke out in an 86th floor shaftway. After it was brought under control, firefighters discovered that it had climbed up to the 102nd floor. The popular observation decks at both those levels had to be closed and some 1,500 tourists evacuated. In addition to forcing other evacuations because of smoke, the fire Friday interrupted broadcasting for several hours by eight FM radio stations whose antennae are atop the building.
