<HEAD>Feud Embarrasses Swedish Leader During Election Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A feud between the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> and the governing <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is proving to be an embarrassment to Prime Minister <PERSON> Ingvar </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> as he campaigns for next month's general election. In the last week, the government's election worries have been compounded by an exchange of accusations with the secret police of mischief-making and political spying. The feud between the government and its counterintelligence arm, known as SAPO, goes back decades. But the tension resurfaced after book publisher and former journalist <PERSON> Ebbe </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> launched his own investigation into the 1986 assassination of Prime Minister <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON>. It became clear the amateur detective, an insider in the governing party, was investigating <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> as much as looking for the elusive killer. But critics said Social Democrats exceeded their authority and sidestepped official channels by ordering the secret investigation, which has overshadowed campaign issues such as taxes or the environment. Justice Minister <PERSON> Anna-Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Leijon </PERSON> resigned last month after it was disclosed that she aided <PERSON> Ebbe </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON>'s efforts to contact British intelligence officials for the investigation. <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> is a department within the regular police structure, and is responsible for ferreting out spies and protecting Cabinet ministers. Palme, who disliked the formalities of office, dismissed his <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> bodyguards when he and his wife went to see a movie on the night he was killed. Prime Minister <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> _ not related to <PERSON> Ebbe </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> _ told a parliamentary inquiry Aug. 4 that he backed the investigation because of `` important allegations and serious criticism against a Swedish authority.'' He was referring to charges that <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> was negligent in protecting <LOCATION> Palme </LOCATION> and tried to cover up its shortcomings in the hunt for the assassin. <PERSON> Ebbe </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> told the inquiry earlier that <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> had failed to act on a tip that <PERSON> Palme </PERSON>'s life was in danger. `` If it is not a conspiracy, it is stupidity,'' he told the televised hearing. In another slap at <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION>, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Sten </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersson </PERSON> told reporters that he trusted <PERSON> Ebbe </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> more than he did <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION>'s commanders `` Palme's murder was for many leading Social Democrats the final confirmation of <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION>'s incompetance,'' said a report in the business weekly Affars Varlden. <PERSON> Holger </PERSON> <PERSON> Romander </PERSON>, a former police chief, was quoted as saying the <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> affair `` is part of a campaign against SAPO ... by people who distrust an organization they can not control and know little about.'' Social Democrats say <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> is a bastion of conservative politics. Some party leaders are reported to back removal of <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> from the police force so that it would report directly to the government. The <ORGANIZATION> Svenska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dagbladet </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> urged the government to reject the credentials last year of a Soviet diplomat whom the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> said was the new <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> station chief. The government ignored their advice. In a book published last week, former <ORGANIZATION> SAPO </ORGANIZATION> chief Per <PERSON> Gunnar </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinge </PERSON> wrote that the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> created a political intelligence agency during the late 1950s. The agency, called the <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, enlisted personnel in military or research organizations to register political opinions of citizens to identify communist sympathizers, the book said. The activity went on until the early 1970s. The <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> story was first published in 1973, and Prime Minister <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> questioned the timing of the book's publication six weeks before the Sept. 18 election The dispute has helped the three opposition parties cooperate in their attempt to unseat the Social Democrats, who have governed <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> for 50 of the last 56 years.
