<HEAD>Media Family Patriarch Dies at 82</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LX4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, the patriarch of a media empire that he sold in 1986 to end a family squabble over control of the holdings, died Monday at age 82. The former owner and publisher of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> had undergone treatment in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> hospitals since learning he had a brain tumor late last year. His doctor said <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> had been in a coma for the past nine days. <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON>, whose newspapers won eight Pulitzer Prizes, sold the two papers in 1986 to <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which folded the Times into The <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION>. Many public figures praised <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON>'s journalistic and financial contributions to <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. `` He was one of our commonwealth's treasures,'' said former Gov. A.B. `` Happy'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, who had his share of feuds with The <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> during his half-century in public life. `` He was respected for his character, integrity, fair-mindedness and benevolence of spirit by those on every side of the controverisal issues of the day,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Ky. `` The tradition he established serves as a continuing memorial to his high sense of journalistic responsibility,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gill </PERSON>, president and publisher of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blodgett </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON>'s personal physician, said he was with <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> when he died at home at 5:15 a.m. `` He had a seizure last weekend, and we believed the tumor was growing again,'' the doctor said. <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> served as president and publisher of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> from December 1937 until June 1971, when his son <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> took over the reins and he became board chairman. Since the sale of the media properties _ including the two papers, a TV station and a printing company, reportedly for $ 435.8 million _ <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> had exercised his influence through the <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> Sr.. Fund <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> and his wife established the philanthropic organization to support education, arts and health endeavors in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. It had distributed more than $ 8 million by late last year. One of the fund's largest gifts was $ 2.6 million for the construction of the 40-story <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fountain </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest floating fountain, which will be dedicated Friday <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> placed the media properties on the market in January 1986 after nearly two years of family infighting. He said he could n't find a solution that was fair to everyone. His illness came as he unsuccessfully fought the release of a controversial book about his father, Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Worth </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON>, who had acquired the newspapers in 1918 with a $ 5 million inheritance from his second wife. The book alleged that the elder <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> contributed to his second wife's death by failing to secure proper medical attention for her and by drugging her to try to persuade her to change her will. <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> dropped the book project after <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> supplied a 5-inch thick memorandum of what he contended were 160 misstatements of fact by author <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Crown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> issued the book in 1987 after making what it called insignificant changes. The Louisville-born <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> with honors in 1928, eventually abandoning his dream of becoming a novelist and joining the newspaper as a police reporter. He took control of the media empire in 1933 when President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Delano </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> appointed his father ambassador to <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Judge <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> had launched WHAS-AM radio in 1922 and later started <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gravure </ORGANIZATION>, which prints Sunday magazine and advertising supplements. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> Sr. set up WHAS-TV in 1950; <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> was involved in opening WAMZ-FM. Dissension within the family surfaced in 1984 when <PERSON> Sallie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> challenged the ability of her brother to serve as editor and publisher. <PERSON> Sallie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON>, her sister <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and their mother were replaced on the board of directors by professional managers. <PERSON> Sallie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> then announced she was disposing of her 15 percent interest. That eventually led to <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON>'s surprise announcement that he was dismantling the empire. In addition to his wife and three children, <PERSON> Bingham </PERSON> is survived by nine grandchildren. Two other sons died in accidents, in 1964 and 1966. A funeral service is scheduled for Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> Calvary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>.
