<HEAD>Speaker To Return 45 Years After Combat Tour, This Time Leading
Delegation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forty-five years after <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> flew a daring World War II bombing mission from a remote Australian airfield, the speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is going back _ this time as the leader of a congressional delegation celebrating the country's bicentennial `` For me it will be a sentimental journey,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said, remembering the 17 hours spent flying over the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> in a stripped-down B-24 and the midnight bombing of refineries at <LOCATION> Balikpapan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Borneo </LOCATION>, where much of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s aviation fuel was being produced. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat was a 19-year-old second lieutenant in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> when he and Capt. <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Connery </PERSON> flew the lead plane in the 2,700-mile mission and suprised the Japanese, who had left the lights on in the harbor at <LOCATION> Balikpapan </LOCATION> because they thought the refineries were beyond the range of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> bombers. On this trip Down Under, he hopes to `` demonstrate to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> our appreciation for their steadfast friendship.'' A meeting with Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> is on <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s itinerary, as the speaker, his wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, and about a dozen members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and their spouses attend ceremonies to inaugurate the new <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in the capital of <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION> The delegation leaves Friday and returns to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Aug. 31, said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who is organizing the bipartisan group at the request of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. While in <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and the delegation will attend the first session of Parliament in the new building and meet with leaders of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and of the opposition party. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lawmakers will visit the Australian War Memorial and the Australian-American War Memorial, and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> will lay a wreath on each. The Australian air force will fly <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to <PERSON> Fenton </PERSON> air strip in the rugged Northern Territory, where he spent much of his combat tour. `` I'll go back for this sentimental journey,'' he said, reminiscing about the time as a young soldier he bought a wild horse from a nearby rancher for $ 48 and fed the animal with oats intended for his comrades' breakfast. He was awarded the Distinguished Flying Cross for his valor in the bombing of the <LOCATION> Balikpapan </LOCATION> oil refineries, at the time the longest bombing mission on record. His plane was the first to arrive over the refineries and the lights immediately went out when he dropped his bombs.
