<HEAD>Stroessner Takes Oath of Office for Eighth Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> took the oath of office for an eighth time Monday in a subdued ceremony that followed weeks of tension between the government and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, 75, was sworn in before the congress by the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Argana </PERSON>. He then quietly walked off the podium without speaking to assembled representatives and foreign dignitaries. The 25-minute ceremony was broadcast by state-run radio across this landlocked and mostly rural country of 3.8 million. Although there were no protests, the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> canceled the annual Te Deum mass of thanksgiving traditionally celebrated on Aug. 15 to mark the anniversary of the founding of the capital, <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>. The cancellation, ordered by Monsignor <PERSON> Ismael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rolon </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>, was a response to the expulsion July 25 of a Spanish Jesuit priest for allegedly publicly encouraging overthrow of the government. The church denied the charge and said the priest, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, a 65-year-old professor, was explaining <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theology </ORGANIZATION>, a movement that advocates political change as a tool of social reform. The church, the most influential institution in the country after the government and the military, claimed in a message delivered from pulpits two weeks ago that it was the victim of persecution. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> urged <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> during a visit here last May to relax restrictions on human rights and political freedom. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, also commander of <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s military, took power in a 1954 coup and has ruled with a heavy hand ever since. His tenure has brought order and modest economic growth to a country that had seen turmoil and 11 different presidents in the 19 years following the end of the Chaco War with <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> in 1935. But most civil liberties are curtailed and dissent is crushed. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> won an eighth term in February in an election marked by the absence of the major opposition groups, and by charges of fraud. He was credited with obtaining 88.6 percent of all votes cast. Monday's inauguration was witnessed by Brazilian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Abreu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sondre </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo </PERSON> and delegations from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Afterward, <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> swore in his 11-member Cabinet. <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Elpidio </PERSON> <PERSON> Acevedo </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Saldivar </PERSON> as foreign minister.
