<HEAD>Soviets Warn Pakistan; Rebels Take District Near Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Inserts 1 graf after 10th `Soviet military' with casualty figures
form Tass and Najib</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will not tolerate more Pakistani aid to Moslem guerrillas in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, who increased pressure on the Soviet-sponsored government by capturing a district near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the capital. Insurgent leader <PERSON> Gulbaddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> that guerrilla successes in the field may cause the Soviets to complete their troop withdrawal ahead of the Feb. 15 deadline. He said his forces had captured <PERSON> Shigal </PERSON>, a strategic post in <LOCATION> Kunar </LOCATION> province near the Pakistani border. A Soviet government statement issued through the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> contained some of the sharpest language the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> has aimed at <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` The Soviet government most resolutely declares that the continuation by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of its obstructionist policy vis-a-vis the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> can not be further tolerated,'' it said. `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reserves for itself, in that case, the right to take such measures that are necessitated by the situation.'' It was not specific about the response. On May 15, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began withdrawing its estimated 115,000 soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> under an agreement signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as guarantors. Half the soldiers were to be out by Aug. 15, which the Soviets said Sunday had been achieved, and all are to be gone by Feb. 15. President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> marked the occasion with an article in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda thanking the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for its help. With the article, Pravda printed a map showing the remaining Soviet soldiers in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> along two evacuation routes, from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Shindand </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Herat </LOCATION> in the west. Soviet military officials said earlier the pullout had cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> from 25 of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s 30 provinces. The map showed soldiers in only a narrow ribbon through the remaining five provinces. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said 31 civilians were killed and 113 wounded in 142 attacks on populated areas in the first 10 days of August. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said at a news conference in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> there are more than 180 guerrilla training centers in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and 50 bases for rearming rebels and storing weapons. The <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement calls for other countries not to interfere in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s internal affairs. Guerrilla groups were not parties to the accord. <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979, replaced one pro-Soviet government with another, and remained to fight the insurgents. More than 13,000 Soviet soldiers have been killed. Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April 1978 and use Pakistani border camps and cities, where more than 3 million Afghan refugees live, as supply points and bases. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries have armed them through <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Monday fighters from insurgent groups had captured the <LOCATION> Shakardar </LOCATION> district about 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. It quoted reports in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> as saying they were armed with 1,500 rockets they intended to aim at the capital. Other guerrilla organizations planned to send large forces armed with `` long-range weapons, rockets and Stinger missiles'' from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Karabag </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pagman </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Sorubi </LOCATION> districts of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> province, the agency said. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, Soviet commander in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, said Sunday that insurgents had captured <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>, a northern provincial capital 40 miles from the Soviet border. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>, who arrived in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Sunday, told a news conference that reports of the fall of <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> were `` fabrication and misinformation.'' When told <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON> announced it, <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> said the general's statement was not `` authentic. `` What is authentic and reliable is the statements made by the government of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Several days ago <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> faced a barbarous and ferocious attack,'' but insurgents could not be considered in control unless they established institutions such as schools and hospitals. `` The fact is that they do not have any kind of administration over there,'' he said. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said Monday soldiers had recaptured the city. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-i-Islami </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas, said his information indicated fighting continued near <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> did not respond directly when asked whether there were circumstances under which the Soviets might stop withdrawing. He cited a joint statement issued Aug. 7 when Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> saying the two sides would `` draw the necessary conclusions and determine their actions'' if <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> continued to aid the insurgents. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said in an interview the same day, however, that the withdrawal would finish on schedule. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> claimed <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> had wanted to remove partial units from eastern, southern and southwestern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to make things easier for Afghan government forces, but that proved too dangerous so entire units have been withdrawn. `` The Soviets are not leaving because of a <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement but because they see no gain,'' he said. `` They are forced to leave.''
