 directions and general clues, can get a running start,'' <PERSON> Malek </PERSON> said. `` We have n't selected yet who is going to give the nominating speeches, for the same reason,'' he said. `` We are developing some ideas of who are good speakers and could do it.'' Part of the problem, <PERSON> Malek </PERSON> said, is whoever nominates the vice presidential candidate must have some logical ties to the person selected and fit within the campaign theme selected by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` There's got to be some kind of a linkage,'' he said. This week's <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> is a carefully scripted affair, and <PERSON> Malek </PERSON> clearly was n't comfortable with leaving major gaps in a schedule that's been developed over months of planning. `` We do n't have any choice,'' <PERSON> Malek </PERSON> said. `` I think it's going to be all right, I think we have the caliber of people to do the nomination. I do n't have any great trepidations about that. Obviously they could do a better job with more time.''
