<HEAD>Gandhi Warns Pakistan Against Helping Sikhs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> warned <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> on Monday against aiding Sikh insurgents in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, saying he did not want to take further action <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> `` might later regret.'' He spoke at celebrations of the 41st anniversary of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> Clashes in <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> state related to the celebrations injured at least 75 people, including 25 police officers, the Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> said. In <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION> state, <PERSON> Popatlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarothia </PERSON>, a legislator of <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, was shot and killed Monday by a disgruntled party worker attending independence festivites, the news agency said <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said at a ceremony in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, `` We have taken firm action against -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- terrorism.'' He did not elaborate. He has often accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of arming and training Sikh rebels who are fighting for a separate homeland in northern <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, which borders <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has offered no proof and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has denied the charge. `` We do not wish to take action -LRB- <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> -RRB- might later regret,'' the prime minister said. He did not refer to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> by name, but said Sikh insurgents were getting help from across the border. On Sunday, Indian border guards shot and killed 11 Pakistanis as they tried to slip across the border into <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION>, authorities said. Sikh radicals have waged a bloody six-year struggle in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, which has claimed about 1,700 lives this year. In <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> state adjoining <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, police fired in the air to disperse pro-Pakistani demonstrators objecting to independence celebrations, <ORGANIZATION> PTI </ORGANIZATION> reported. It said demonstrators burned a police jeep, threw stones at police and forced shops to close, with at least 75 people hurt. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> was part of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> until 1947. Since their joint independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the two nations have fought each other in three wars. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> controls 30 percent of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION>, but claims the entire state as its own. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> rejects the claim. At least 2,500 security officers were on duty as <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> delivered his Independence Day address at the 16th-century <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, according to a police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Guests, including Cabinet ministers and foreign diplomats, were frisked before the 40-minute ceremony and sharpshooters were posted on tall buildings around the sandstone fort. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, wearing white trousers and a tunic, unfurled the Indian flag on the ramparts of the fort to begin the festivities. He referred in his speech to the nearby island nation of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, where about 47,000 Indian soldiers are deployed to enforce a July 29, 1987, peace accord aimed at ending a five-year rebellion by Tamil insurgents. Tamil rebels returned to combat after a brief truce and are fighting Indian troops. `` We hope that the accord will be speedily implemented,'' <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said. A major reason for <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s brokering the accord was that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has 60 million Tamils of its own, who are sympathetic to the Sri Lankan rebel cause. Tamils make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and claim discrimination by the majority Sinhalese population. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s diplomatic mission in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, is under heavy security after intelligence reports that a Tamil assassination squad entered the capital.
