<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSContacts     08-15 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Contacts,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tracing Sexual, Drug Partners of AIDS-Infected People Called
Premature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Health officials are premature in embracing programs to trace sexual and needle-sharing partners of people infected with the AIDS virus, researchers said Monday. Such programs are required by the federal government as a condition of grants to states for AIDS programs. But there is little evidence such programs curb the spread of the virus, the researchers said at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In response, a government public health expert defended the programs as a way to get education to people a high risk of infection. `` We have to try and make education work,'' said <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> <PERSON> Havlak </PERSON> of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. The virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome can be spread by sex or sharing of needles used to inject drugs. One goal of notification is to limit the spread of infection, by uncovering people who do not realize they carry the virus and persuading them to act accordingly. But evidence is lacking that notification affects virus spread, said <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Dejowski </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. So it is premature to adopt widespread notification, he said. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Havlak </PERSON> said that while the brief counseling that surrounds a notification will not be enough to make a person change his behavior, that counseling is `` only the beginning.'' Long-term counseling and support are needed to bring about behavior change, he said. Many parts of the country have yet to develop such programs, he added. <PERSON> Dejowski </PERSON> also said the workings of some notification programs raise questions about the rights of notified people. One city's notifiers ask to draw blood for a test from the person at the time he is notified, he said. The contacted person, having just heard `` overwhelming'' information from a stranger, may not be able to properly consider that request, <PERSON> Dejowski </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Havlak </PERSON> called the point arguable, but said the notifiers offer on-the-spot testing only as an option. Distraught people are offered crisis intervention help rather than being forced to decide on the blood test, he said. <PERSON> Dejowski </PERSON> also criticized pending federal legislation that would make states and local governments allow notification of spouses to be done by medical personnel. Such notification lacks the control and accountability of programs by public agencies, he said. And there is no guarantee that a doctor, nurse or other medical professional would have the training and sensitivity to deliver the news properly, he said. <PERSON> Havlak </PERSON> said he knows of no state that now prevents doctors from doing such notifications. Doctors can get help from state health departments if they wish, he said.
