<HEAD>Historian Gives Sympathetic Picture of `Prague Spring'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet historian says the goals of the Czechoslovak reforms Soviet tanks crushed 20 years ago were similar to those now pursued by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. L.S. <PERSON> Yagodovsky </PERSON>'s article in the latest issue of the weekly journal <ORGANIZATION> Arguments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facts </ORGANIZATION> contrasted dramatically with previous characterizations of the the `` <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> spring'' led by <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, which ended with a Soviet-led invasion Aug. 21, 1968. As recently as January, the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said comparisons with current Soviet reforms were the work of Western propaganda. <PERSON> Yagodovsky </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> of the Economy of the World Socialist System, used such <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> words as `` restructuring,'' `` glasnost,'' `` self-management,'' and `` self-financing'' to describe the Czechoslovak reforms. Reforms adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Czechoslovak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1965 `` coincide with the basic principles of today's transformation in this area in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, as with the conception of economic reform existing at this time in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other socialist countries,'' he said in the Aug. 13-19 edition of the journal. He said <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, then the Soviet leader, was more sympathethic to conservative opponents, and in the end reformers let the situation get out of control. <PERSON> Yagodovsky </PERSON> quoted party documents that said no way existed to restore order in the country except to invite the invasion. He said conservatives backed by party chief <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Novotny </PERSON> blocked the reforms and they could not succeed without `` perestroika of the form and methods of party work, without democratization of society, affirmation of glasnost -LRB- openness -RRB-, without giving socialism genuine human lines.'' <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Novotny </PERSON> as party leader in January 1968, and in March <PERSON> Ludvik </PERSON> <PERSON> Svoboda </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Novotny </PERSON> as president. Further reforms put in place in January and April 1968 `` opened the way for normalization of the situation, uniting the leading forces in a platform of renewal,'' <PERSON> Yagodovsky </PERSON> said, but <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> and other party leaders did not take advantage of it. `` One of the main reasons, in my view, is that despite the rearrangement in the government, unity in the Presidium of the <ORGANIZATION> Czechoslovak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and in the party as a whole, was not guaranteed,'' he said. All top officials wanted reforms but did not agree on what the reforms meant, he said. `` Anti-socialist forces'' inside and outside <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> became more active and the situation in the country deteriorated sharply, he said. <PERSON> Yagodovsky </PERSON> quoted Czechoslovak party documents as saying the party was paralyzed, the government on the brink of decay and there was no choice but to bring in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact force to restore order. <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> was replaced as Czechoslovak party leader in April 1969 by <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON>, who retired last year after running one of the Soviet bloc's more conservative organizations for nearly a generation.
