<HEAD>Parish That Experimented With Lay Participation Loses Official
Sanction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An experimental Roman Catholic parish that offered extensive lay participation such as planning the liturgy went out of official existence Monday, but its members vowed to carry on. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Corley </PERSON>, a lay trustee of the Genesis Community, said the 13-year-old group would continue in some form despite <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelineau </PERSON>'s decision to disband it as a formal church-sanctioned group. `` After today, the bishop has told us that we can not have a priest and a Eucharist celebrated on Sunday morning,'' <PERSON> Corley </PERSON> said. `` We will be following the bishop's directive over the next 40 days. We will not get together as a community for Eucharist celebration on Sunday morning.'' The group will meet on Sunday nights for `` prayer, reflection and discussion'' and will decide at the end of the 40 days where to proceed, <PERSON> Corley </PERSON> said. Last month, <PERSON> Gelineau </PERSON>, who created the Genesis Community 13 years ago, announced it would be dissolved after a task force he commissioned found it beset with `` erroneous attitudes'' concerning church teaching. <PERSON> Corley </PERSON> said the group was consulting canon lawyers to see whether <PERSON> Gelineau </PERSON>'s decision could be appealed. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diocese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Providence </ORGANIZATION>, said he did not think an appeal was possible. `` They're an experimental open worship community that was a creation of the diocese, so it's strictly a diocesan internal matter,'' <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> said. `` My understanding is that their only appeal would be to the bishop,'' he said. `` I do n't think there's any provision where they could go over his head _ to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, for example.'' The Genesis Community, unlike most Catholic parishes, was open to <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION> regardless of where in the state they lived. <PERSON> Corley </PERSON> said it was distinguished by the role lay people played in `` sitting down with the priest, planning liturgy, social justice concerns.'' Conflicts between the group and its most recent priest, the Rev. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Scagnelli </PERSON>, led <PERSON> Gelineau </PERSON> to commission the task force that recommended ending the experiment. <PERSON> Corley </PERSON> said the conflicts included whether leavened or unleavened bread would be used during the Eucharist ceremony and whether lay people as well as priests could read from the Gospel or deliver homilies. He said the community gave in to <PERSON> Scagnelli </PERSON> on each of those issues, but with each concession, some members became more and more disturbed. Some members said the degree of lay participation was what drew them to Genesis and warned that the church's resistance to the idea would be self-defeating. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is not the cathedral. It's not the clergy. It's us. It's the people,'' said member <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotter </PERSON>. `` I ca n't see myself going back to the parish I left 13 years ago.''
