 for allegedly starting a fight over a sandwich. That was only one of a number of scrapes with the law <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> has had since May 1985, when <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> commuted his sentence on the original rape conviction to the six years <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> had already served. In commuting his sentence, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> bypassed <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s request for clemency, saying he did not believe <PERSON> Mrs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s recantation nor <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s denials. Since that 1985 release, <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>, 30, has been in jail several times, convicted of drunken-driving charges and arrested for allegedly punching his wife and threatening the couple's infant daughter. Under the good-behavior terms of <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s `` last-chance'' order, <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> will remain under parole supervision for three years and will undergo treatment for an admitted drinking problem. <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> will be released Tuesday into an intensive residential treatment program for `` an unspecified period of time'' and will continue to receive out-patient counseling for his alcohol problem, said <PERSON> Nic </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> suggested Monday that <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s run-ins with the law may have stemmed from his original imprisonment, and that recent tests performed by a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> forensic serologist prove `` conclusively, absolutely and definitively that <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> did not have sex with <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>.'' Results of the test, which involve DNA analysis of blood and semen samples from <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> and her former boyfriend, were turned over to <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> by <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s staff. Dr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON>, who performed the tests, said in a telephone interview Monday from the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> area that the test `` demonstrates that the semen in <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s panties did not come from <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>, but was compatible with that of her boyfriend.'' He said results of the test, called Polymerase Chain Reaction, were submitted in one criminal case in which he testified in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state courts and were not legally challenged by either prosecutors or the defense. He said he was uncertain whether <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> courts would allow test results to be submitted as evidence. The actual clemency request <PERSON> Breen </PERSON> made Monday is submitted to the prison review board, which makes a recommendation and passes the request on to the governor.
