<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Asks Tibet To Remove Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> said Monday that during a visit to <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> he expressed concern about human rights violations and asked the region's government to lift restrictions on foreign journalists and other travelers. Ambassador <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said he told <PERSON> Doje </PERSON> <PERSON> Cering </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Tibet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Autonomous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>, that `` if they want to have informed reporting they ought to let in journalists as well as anyone else.'' Lord visited the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> and the city of <LOCATION> Xigaze </LOCATION> Aug. 4-10. He was the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to visit the remote western region. <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, ruled by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, has been closed to all but a few selected foreign reporters since pro-independence riots in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> last fall and again in March. <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> had been trying to build a tourist industry, but it also banned individual travelers, permitting only organized group tours, after the violence. Fourteen foreign reporters who went to <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> to cover the October riots were expelled from <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said <PERSON> Doje </PERSON> <PERSON> Cering </PERSON> `` seemed responsive.'' He did not elaborate. The ambassador said that in his two-hour meeting with <PERSON> Doje </PERSON> <PERSON> Cering </PERSON> he also brought up the issues of human rights and the status of prisoners detained after the disturbances. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> accused the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of interfering in its internal affairs after the passage of several congressional resolutions last year calling for an end to human rights violations in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said <PERSON> Doje </PERSON> <PERSON> Cering </PERSON> told him that the human rights situation has improved in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> since the Chinese Communists ended the theocracy headed by the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, the spiritual head of Tibetan Buddhism. <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> came under <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military and political control in 1950-51. The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> fled to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> after a failed nationalist revolt in 1959 and <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> was made an autonomous region of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1965. Lord noted the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recognizes <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s sovereignty over the region. The anti-Chinese demonstrations in October 1987 and last March were led by Tibetan monks loyal to the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>. They accuse the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government of undermining Tibetan social and religious customs. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said <PERSON> Doje </PERSON> <PERSON> Cering </PERSON> told him that only 25 or 26 of the more than 200 people detained after the March rioting remained in prison, and eight of those still jailed were <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks or nuns. It is beleved several dozen people were killed during the violence in March. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said he asked permission for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official to visit a jail but there was no immediate response.
