<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The police chief Monday yielded to pressure from civil rights leaders and rescinded a policy requiring officers to randomly stop black youths in a racially mixed neighborhood. Chief <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Felker </PERSON> issued an order July 8 that police stop and question groups of black teen-agers in what he called an effort to end racial violence in <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION> neighborhood. `` The procedure was implemented to address a series of crimes that had been committed,'' <PERSON> Felker </PERSON> said in a statement Monday afternoon. `` Unfortunately, the focus of the directive has been perceived as racially motivated instead of the intent of focusing on the suspects involved.'' The statement apparently was issued to clarify reports earlier Monday that <PERSON> Felker </PERSON> had just dropped the word `` black'' from his directive. The statement said he had rescinded the order and directed his officers to return to normal procedures of stopping people only if police believe reasonable cause exists. <PERSON> Felker </PERSON>'s decision followed meetings with the president of the Toledo chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People, city officials and neighborhood residents. A group of black lawyers hailed <PERSON> Felker </PERSON>'s decision but said a $ 1 million federal lawsuit against the city would not be withdrawn. `` The suit will continue, and we expect more plaintiffs to join us. The policy was patently racist,'' said <PERSON> Lafayette </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolliver </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Thurgood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The group filed the lawsuit Friday on behalf of <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a black teen-ager w