<HEAD>Quayle Says He Worries About Candidacy's Effect on His Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said Monday he would be <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate if asked, but that `` from a personal standpoint'' he would n't choose to run for national office this year. The <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator, said to be on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s short list of prospective vice presidential nominees, said he has reservations about his candidacy's effect on his family. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, 41, is married and has three children. `` From a personal standpoint, if I had a time in my life to be vice president, I would n't choose this time,'' he said. But, he added: `` If <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> thinks I can offer the most to the ticket ... <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> will sign up immediately.'' His wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, also said she has reservations about `` the total lack of privacy.'' Whether her husband gets the nomination or not `` it's fine,'' she said. `` I'm not panting after it.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said his 14-year-old son, <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, is fascinated by the prospect of his father running for vice president. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s 11-year-old son, is ambiguous, his father said, and 9-year-old <PERSON> Corinne </PERSON> does n't like the idea of her father spending more time away from home. `` She told me, ` Daddy, I really hope <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> picks <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>,''' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` I said, ` It may happen.''' In case he is selected, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has begun to think about an acceptance speech to the Republican National Convention. `` I have n't sat down to write. I think that would be bad luck,'' he said. `` But I do have some ideas.''
