<HEAD>Panamanians Pay Homage At Funeral Of Three-time President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to include more details on anti-government
protest. PICKS up 7th pvs: The government offered...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of people turned the funeral for three-time President <PERSON> Arnulfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON> into a huge but peaceful anti-government demonstration Monday. It was one of the largest demonstrations in 14 months of protests against the rule of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who commands <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and controls the civilian government. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> was elected three times and overthrown each time by the military. He died Wednesday in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, who would would have been 87 Monday, spent more time in jail and exile than in office but was credited with founding <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s social security system and introducing women's suffrage. A vast crowd gathered in the plaza in front of the Metropolitan Cathedral for the funeral that was conducted from the church steps. As the service ended and the coffin was placed aboard a firetruck a roar went up from the crowd, with the people repeatedly shouting `` Justice!'' Thousands of people followed the cortege out of the plaza, through the narrow streets of the old section of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and onto Central Avenue, for the three-mile journey to a cemetery. With each block te procession became longer until people filled the four-lane avenue for nearly a mile. `` Arnulfo president, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> criminal!'' people in the crowd shouted. `` <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> must go.'' Many people waved white banners, a sign of protest in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, or the flags of political parties opposed to <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> who was indicted by two federal grand juries in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> last February on charges of narcotics trafficking. The government offered to provide military honors at the funeral but the <ORGANIZATION> Authentic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> founded in 1935, refused. Instead, the party decided on the requiem Mass conducted on the cathedral steps by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON>, the Roman Catholic archbishop. `` We ca n't accept that those who always overthrew the doctor -LRB- <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> -RRB- share in our grief,'' said <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Artola </PERSON>, party vice president. `` The ceremony is going to be for the people.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s soldiers and police, who have crushed dozens of protests in the past 14 months, did not interfere with the funeral despite the anti-government tone. Firefighters helped control the cathedral crowd and one of their bright orange ladder trucks carried the flag-draped coffin to the Garden of Peace cemetery. All sides in this politically divided country claimed <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> as their own. Government-controlled newspapers referred vaguely to his `` errors'' during 57 years in politics, but praised his nationalism and defiance of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and his daughter, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON>, were among the mourners Monday. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> was first turned out of office by a military coup July 14, 1941, after serving 9 -LCB- months of a four-year term. In January of that year, he had rejected a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> request for land for military bases along the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. Soon after <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> was deposed at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s urging, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> provided 37,000 acres for the bases. He was elected again in 1949 but tossed out by the army in 1951. He began his third elected term Oct. 1, 1968, but was overthrown 11 days later in a coup led by Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrijos </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> replaced as head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces. Four years ago <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> ran for president again and lost to <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardito </PERSON> <PERSON> Barletta </PERSON>, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s candidate, in an election widely viewed as fraudulent. The government said <PERSON> Ardito </PERSON> <PERSON> Barletta </PERSON> won by 1,713 votes. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> died of a heart attack. He had gone to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> for medical treatment last April and remained there until his death.
