</TEXT>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Honored at GOP Luncheon</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> surprised his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, with an unscheduled appearance Monday at a luncheon in her honor. `` I really ca n't imagine these last eight years without <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>,'' he said. `` She once said the president has all kinds of advisers and experts ... when it comes to foreign policy, the economy or whatever, but no one to look after his needs as a human being. Well, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> has done that.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, moist-eyed at the tribute, said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has given <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> and me eight of the most wonderful years we have ever had.'' But she added, `` Today the curtain begins to close on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> era of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. We have had a wonderful run, but today it is time for the Bushes to step into the political leading roles and for the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> to step into the wings.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Bush Readies Acceptance Speech</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, putting the finishing touches on his speech accepting the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nomination, conceded that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will be a tough act to follow. But he said he hoped to put his own stamp on the convention and `` not try to be a <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. There is only one.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> planned to watch <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s speech to the convention on television at the vice presidential residence in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> before flying to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> on Tuesday.
