<HEAD>Potential Running Mates Make the Rounds</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Potential Republican vice presidents made a whirlwind round of appearances Monday, some openly touting their qualifications, others playing coy. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he still had n't made up his mind. Senate Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> said he and his wife, former <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, left a message on their telephone answering machine back in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>: `` Just in case they got the wrong number. It just says, ` I accept.''' Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> told the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> delegation, `` I'm here because <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> knows who I am. He decided to put me on a list.'' And Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> told reporters, `` I would be a terrific campaigner and a terrific candidate and a terrific vice president.''
