<HEAD>Party's Also-Rans Step Into Spotlight _ Briefly</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Once bickering rivals taking aim on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s shortcomings, the five men he bested in the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> primaries assembled here this week to sing his praises, attack <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and _ in at least one case _ pull a surprise. <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> improbably beckoned the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the Democratic runner-up, to switch to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>. `` We need you and you need us,'' du <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> said. `` As long as you have breath yours will be a prominent voice, but as long as you speak as a Democrat, you will never be a successful leader.'' The proposal was greeted with silence by delegates. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> contrasted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` safe and progressive'' policies with those of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, whom he called the `` diminutive clerk from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> and <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> spoke at Monday's opening morning session. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> will speak in evening sessions on prime-time TV.
