<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Israeli F-15 jet fighters on a training flight collided over the <LOCATION> Dead </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> area Monday and both pilots were killed, the military command reported. It said Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Avihu </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin-Nun </PERSON>, the air force commander, appointed a commission to investigate. The announcement was held up about 12 hours and gave no further details. Strict censorship delays release of information on events considered to involve national security. The army identified the pilots as Maj. <PERSON> Ehud </PERSON> <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> of the northern Israeli kibbutz, or communal settlement, of <LOCATION> Merhavya </LOCATION>, and Lt. Col. <PERSON> Ram </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuller </PERSON> of the northern kibbutz of <PERSON> Kfar </PERSON> <PERSON> Giladi </PERSON>. Informed sources in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said it was the first known accident <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s air force has had with the high-flying American-built Eagle. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has about 50 of the planes, manufactured by the <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and ordered five more earlier in the summer. They were used with deadly force in an air war with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> a decade ago. More than 80 Syrian jets were shot down. None of the Israeli F-15s were lost. The lopsided Israeli victory, and triumphs in other wars with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> enemies, has created an aura of pride and proficiency envied by other air forces around the world. Two other F-15s, owned by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, crashed last June. The planes cost about $ 30 million apiece. Normally, Israeli training exercises with the high-flying jets are conducted over the <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> desert in the southern area of the country, but speculation about Monday's accident centered on the Israeli-held West bank. The F-15, nicknamed the Eagle by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, is the most advanced, land-based jet fighter in the American inventory. The twin-engine jet is designed to fly and fight in all weather conditions and can soar at more than 2 -LCB- times the speed of sound. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is one of few foreign countries that has been allowed to acquire the plane. Even so, the Eagles in its possession are not the most advanced version of the F-15 produced by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>. In recent years, the F-15's safety record has helped the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> reduce its overall accident rate to some of the lowest marks ever. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has had three mid-air mishaps involving F-15s this year, but in each case the plane was only damaged, managed to land without further incident and there were no fatalities. Overall, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said, there have been 15 mid-air accidents. The F-15 was first flown in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1972 and was delivered to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> combat squadrons beginning in 1976. Since then, the Eagle has chalked up an overall accident rate of 3.0 mishaps per 100,000 flight hours, which for a jet fighter is very low. The F-15 is normally armed with one internal 20mm cannon and two types of air-to-air `` dogfighting'' missiles, the Sparrow and Sidewinder. The single-seat fighter has a combat altitude ceiling of 65,000 feet.
