<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An estimated 5,000 people claiming the July elections were fraudulent clogged the steps of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> building Monday as legislators began the process of certifying election results. The crowd parted as <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, presidential candidate of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, arrived to address <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. People showered <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> with confetti and shouted insults at the governing <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, known as the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> told the legislators: `` What we are asking the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> is one thing _ responsibility. `` We are asking that the elections be cleaned up ... of the innumerable irregularities committed in the electoral process principally by representatives of the official party, by municipal, state and federal authorities.'' The 64-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and 500 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> serve as the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, and the session is scheduled to run through Aug. 31. Senators will certify election results for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats and the deputies will certify the results for seats in the lower house. The Chamber of Deputies then will certify the count in the presidential balloting. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> won the presidential contest with 50.36 percent of the vote. It said <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> governor and senator who broke with the party last year over democratic reform, received 31.12 percent, and <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON>, candidate of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, obtained 17.07 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> has governed <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since 1929, dominating both national and state politics, and it is virtually certain that the legislators will name <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> president-elect in the final stage of this year's election process. The new president will be inaugurated Dec. 1, replacing President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON> who is completing his six-year term and could not run for re-election under Mexican law. For the first two weeks of the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> session the legislators will review the results of the congressional races. The results for 26 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> and at least one <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat are being challenged. Both right-wing and left-wing parties have accused the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> of fraud in the July 6 elections and have held protest rallies almost daily. Opposition leaders claim the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> cheated at the polling places and doctored the voter registration rolls and totals released by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Despite the allegations, the election may have been the most open since the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> was founded in 1929. For the first time, the opposition won seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, gaining four although one is being challenged. And the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> will have have to contend with at least 227 opposition deputies in the lower house, which has been expanded from 400 to 500 seats. The <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> had 289 seats in the old, 400-seat chamber. The final count depends on the certification of the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. In all previous presidential races the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> presidential candidate received at least 70 percent of the vote. The opposition is awaiting with particular interest the separate returns on the presidential race from about 25,000 of the nation's nearly 55,000 polling places, which the election commission did not make public The commission, after a week-long delay, announced overall totals, saying <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, a 40-year-old former budget director, had won, but it made public the tallies from only about 30,000 polling places.
