<HEAD>U.N. Committee Hears Debate On Puerto Rico's Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Puerto Rican speakers showed their deep divisions at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Monday over whether statehood, independence or keeping the island's status as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commonwealth was the answer to its economic woes. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Decolonization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is holding hearings this week on <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s status, athough the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> already has rejected the committee as anti-American. A diplomat on the committee, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the committee probably will issue a resolution Wednesday calling for self-determination for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Felice </PERSON>, from an organization called the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> for the Rights and <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> has become poorer than any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> state and should be granted independence. But <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, a member of a group called <ORGANIZATION> Puerto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ricans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statehood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, told the committee <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> would benefit more by achieving statehood. <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> said the island still could preserve its Spanish culture. Other speakers said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was actively trying to block the pro-independence movement. Cuban Ambassador <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Oramas-Oliva </PERSON> introduced a resolution which noted allegations that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> was using surveillance to keep track of Puerto Rican independence activists. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> seized <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> in 1898 during the Spanish-American War. Puerto Ricans are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. In 1952, Puerto Rican voters overwhelmingly passed a referendum favoring commonwealth status, and the following year the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> removed <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> from its list of colonies. Since 1973, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Decolonization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has adopted numerous resolutions calling <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> an illegal colony and demanding self-determination for its people. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> rejected those resolutions as interference in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> internal affairs, and in 1971 walked off the committee, saying it had an anti-American bias. Pro-statehood speakers told the committee Monday that 95 percent of the island's voters rejected independence in a 1984 election and that the solution to poverty is to make <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> the 51st <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> state. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Susler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> described the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attitude toward the commonwealth as colonial, saying pro-independence advocates are added to blacklists compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and shared with the Puerto Rican police. She said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> used the grand jury system to compel friends and family members of pro-independence advocates to testify about their activities or face jail, `` a method to politically intern Puerto Rican independence activists.'' A pro-statehood advocate, <PERSON> Elsie </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdes </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Movimiento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unidos </ORGANIZATION> ante la Incertidumbre -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> against Uncertainty -RRB-, said Spanish would not atrophy in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. Rather, she said, mainland <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will become bilingual in English and Spanish, with <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> leading the way. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Vizcarrondo </PERSON> <PERSON> Irizarry </PERSON> spoke for keeping the commonwealth. He said the present U.S.-Puerto Rico relationship should be maintained and developed, but he questioned whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> desired to really improve the economy of the island.
