<HEAD>Lawmakers Near Reforms Inspired By FBI Corruption Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with conference committee agreement, details; picks up
next-to-last graf pvs `The House...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators reported reaching a compromise Monday on a county government reorganization bill inspired in part by an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> corruption investigation in which 56 county supervisors were charged. After doubts earlier in the day on whether differences could be settled between versions the two chambers approved in a special legislative session, chief <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiator <PERSON> Ollie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> said an agreement was reached. He said it would be brought before the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for approval Tuesday. `` I did not want to be held responsible, as I was held responsible last May, that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> killed the bill,'' he said. The plan to restructure county government stemmed from an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation of corrupt county purchasing practices that led to federal charges ranging from mail fraud to extortion against 56 supervisors in 25 counties. Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> called the special session to consider instituting countywide administration in place of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s unique system in which most counties are split into districts in which locally elected supervisors govern decisions such as purchasing and road maintenance <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> said his conferees had backed off a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> provision that would have required counties to purchase at least 10 percent of equipment, supplies and services from businesses owned by minorities and women. He said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> conferees had accepted a provision granting `` home rule'' to counties, but senators had allowed to be stricken language prohibiting them from entering collective bargaining agreements. Under home rule, counties would be allowed to take actions not specifically prohibited by law. Under current statutes, they may take only those actions expressly permitted. Cities were granted home rule in 1985. <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> said negotiators had accepted the House language on the wording of a referendum for voters to decide if their counties would maintain roads on a countywide or district basis. He said they had `` split'' on <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> language that would have exempted from the referendum requirement those counties that were in `` substantial compliance'' with provisions of the bill on Oct. 1. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> agreed that a county supervisor could not serve as county administrator, road manager, purchasing clerk, receiving clerk or inventory clerk. Of the 56 supervisors charged, 42 have pleaded guilty, six have been convicted, one has been acquitted, one died before going to trial, one died after sentencing, and another was declared mentally incompetent to stand trial. The remaining ones still have charges pending.
