<HEAD>Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan Urges Economic Reform and Openness</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The heir to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s throne is a prince who fosters economic reform and political openness for his nation in the midst of <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> turmoil. `` There has been a continous cry on my part ... for a need to think seriously of Jordanian perestroika,'' said <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON>, referring to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s plans to revitalize Soviet society. The 41-year-old younger brother of King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> is regarded as one of the Arab world's most visible intellectuals. For two decades, the Oxford-educated prince has guided development planning in this country of 2.8 million people. He has overseen remarkable economic growth in a land blessed by education but nearly barren of natural resources. With an economic slump squeezing the region, <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> has urged bureaucratic reforms and calls for economic policies aimed at making the Hashemite desert kingdom a center for services and technology. <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> sees economic success as a major element of identity for his 40-year-old country, along with his family's 1,000-year history as rulers of Mecca. He said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the task of rebuilding <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> following the disastrous 1967 war with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, which flooded the country with refugees, was one of `` restating <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s credibility on the basis of merit; that <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> is a country that works.'' He also describes the war as his greatest trauma. Most of his published works have been devoted to the Palestine problem, urging a moderate road to <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> peace. About half or more of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s population are Palestinians; most of the remainder are <PERSON> Bedouin </PERSON> <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON>, like King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> and <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s failure in its efforts for <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> peace led King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> in early August to renounce responsibility for the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> on the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s decision is expected to force <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> to forge a new identity for itself, one in which <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> likely would play a role because of his leadership of the kingdom's economic and research institutions. The prince himself is key to the survival of the last Hashemite monarchy. His family, descended from <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s Prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, once ruled <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> as well as <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. It led the Arabs to independence from Ottoman <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> in a World War I alliance with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. His patronage of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s intellectual and business communities, as well as his periodic tours of army installations, are partly designed to help broaden his base in a country so closely identified with its ruler that a common cliche says: `` King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> is King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> was an Oxford undergraduate in Oriental studies when <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> named him crown prince in 1965. He said his Oxford years were `` definitely the happiest years of my life,'' and an academic aura still clings to him. He described himself as `` a magpie reader,'' sampling a wide range of subjects. But he said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s book, `` Perestroika,'' was the most fascinating thing he had read lately _ along with <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> philosopher <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s `` In Praise of Idleness.'' Short, stocky and athletic, the prince seldom seems idle. He spends his spare time practicing Chinese martial arts, playing squash or polo, and with his family. The prince has four children by his Pakistani-born wife, Princess <PERSON> Tharwat </PERSON>, but none have a direct line to the throne. King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> has decreed that his own third son, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Aly </PERSON>, is in line after <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON>. Jordanian television often shows <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> addressing two or three seminars or conferences a day in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, or attending international conferences on development or humanitarian affairs. He helped found most of the country's chief think tanks, and said he enjoys seminars where he can step out of his palace role. `` Nobody's going to stand up to a person of authority and express their views as clearly as they should,'' he said. <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> has repeatedly urged freer debate on domestic policy issues, occasionally bumping heads with government officials concerned about criticism. The prince said <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> should `` emphasize our basic renewable resource, which is creative thought and political will based on an openness which I think has characterized King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s style.'' He has also prodded Arabs to develop their own `` centers of excellence'' and said he was `` somewhat resentful'' of the Western dominance of Middle Eastern studies. `` I think that regional self-reliance in the intellectual field is the only way of tempering that -LRB- Western -RRB- naivite, which is welcome in terms of its innocence but tiresome in terms of its clumsiness,'' he said.
