<HEAD>Flattened in War, Dresden Still Struggling to Recapture Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DRESDEN, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The charred skeletons of a once magnificent city center still dominate <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>'s patchwork skyline of hasty postwar renewal and piecemeal restoration. City planners acknowledge and many <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION> residents complain that the pace of restoration has been slowed because <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, has been given priority in rebuilding efforts <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>, known as the `` German Florence'' before its almost total destruction in two days of Allied firebombing raids in 1945, is today a city of stark, often brutal contrasts. Viewed from the far end of the old <LOCATION> Augustus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> over the <LOCATION> Elbe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, the meticulously rebuilt Semper opera house, Roman Catholic cathedral and Zwinger Gallery stand next to the bombed-out and scorched ruins of the once majestic Royal Palace. Despite initial restoration efforts, the palace's crumbling and roofless facades remain in large part home for birds and overgrown vegetation. Featureless, Soviet-style housing and commercial blocks erected after World War II now dominate the city's main thoroughfares and plazas, interspersed with vast and idle spaces long since cleared of rubble. Most of the city's once fabled Baroque turrets and spires are gone. Nevertheless, city officials are fiercely proud of the restoration projects undertaken in recent years. But they say much work has been slowed because of lack of resources. Many grumbling Dresdeners blame the restoration delays and the widespread deterioration of many buildings that survived on poor planning and breakneck efforts to spruce up <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. More than 20,000 construction workers were ordered to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> last year to work on massive building projects as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials strove to compete with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s glitter during the city's 750th anniversary celebrations. East German officials, in an effort to make <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> a showcase, have diverted building materials and workers to the capital for years, leaving many provincial cities to struggle to find the means to restore thousands of crumbling buildings. <PERSON> Karl-Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Seltmann </PERSON>, an official in <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>'s city administration responsible for culture, defended the allocation of resources. `` The capital city is the capital city,'' he said. Others say the city _ and the nation _ faced an awesome reconstruction task after World War II. `` You have to remember that this city was raised from 15 million cubic meters of total ruin,'' said <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON>, director general of <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>'s 11 state musuems, referring to the firestorm that devastated the city Feb. 13-14, 1945. The destruction of <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION> in the final days of the war has prompted debate among military historians about the necessity of the raids at a time when the Soviet army was already rapidly advancing into <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The city, a communications and rail link, was swollen with refugees and estimates of the death toll have ranged from 35,000 to more than 135,000. The city and its destruction figured prominently in author <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Vonnegut </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s internationally acclaimed 1969 novel, `` Slaughterhouse Five.'' <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> said the devastation did not break the city's will to survive. `` <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION> residents turned out to help rebuild the Zwinger Gallery when many of them still had no homes to return to.'' He added that the city had accomplished much, despite the subsequent shortages. He said city pride and a deep-rooted sense of cultural tradition has helped <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION> recover much of its reputation as a city once legendary for its art, architecture and music. Most of <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>'s art treasures escaped wartime destruction, <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> said, because they were hidden by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in more than 50 locations around the state of <LOCATION> Saxony </LOCATION>. Many were discovered in poor condition in a damp mine shaft by Soviet troops, <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> said. `` The Russians preserved them and returned them to us.'' He said more than 1,240 paintings were returned but about 500 works are still missing, including two Rembrandts. The treasures of the Saxon royalty, known as the <PERSON> Gruene </PERSON> <PERSON> Gewoelbe </PERSON>, also survived the the war intact and are on display at the state art gallery. The collection contains more than 3,000 stunningly crafted works in gold, silver, ivory, ebony, amber, brass, and bronze. Many are lavishly decorated with precious stones. <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> said he hoped shortages that have slowed restoration of the Royal Palace can be overcome and that work can be completed by the turn of the century. The palace will be the repository of many of the city's art treasures now in storage because of a lack of gallery space. But some of the city's most dramatic restoration achievements are already in peril because of air pollution. Heavily-laden diesel trucks and cars using oil-laced gasoline roar past Theater Square, belching clouds of exhaust fumes around the opera and <LOCATION> Zwinger </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gallery </LOCATION>, coating the buildings with a film of grimy, black soot. Emissions from a coal-fired power plant not far away also threaten the sandstone and granite facades.
