<HEAD>Bruce Lee's Successor Refuses to Be Another Rambo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chan </PERSON>, the successor to the legendary chop and drop king <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s top action film star, has yet to crack the American market but insists he has more to offer than <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> `` Rambo'' <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON>. `` I think I am far better than him _ I dare say it straight to his face _ because I can do things he can, but he ca n't do things I can,'' the baby-faced <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> boasted in a recent interview. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON>, 34, is famous throughout <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> for the death-defying stunts liberally sprinkled throughout his movies, and he pooh-poohs the `` Rambo'' series because <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON> does n't attempt such exploits. `` We see the cave explode and then there he is, appearing on top of another hill. Really, Rambo,'' he said. `` I only do what I really can, something an ordinary man can not do but a trained man can. This is me,'' <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> said, proudly tapping his chest. In the 1987 film `` Project A II,'' <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> jumped from a 50-foot clock tower to the concrete ground through two flimsy canvases. It was a typical example of his work. Such stunts, however, do n't come without bruises. In July, he knocked himself out during a scene in which he somersaulted on top of a moving bus before smashing through a billboard. The combination of stunts and humor in <LOCATION> Chan </LOCATION>'s movies have made him a smash box-office success in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, with his last 10 movies earning more than $ 150 million in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. At the same time, Jackie-mania is ever present. When he appeared for a promotion in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in March, 800 fans turned up, and he topped a list of idols in a survey of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> teen-agers released in February. In 1987, a Japanese woman moved to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to serve him tea in his studio every day. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> made her his floor manager, a move that drove dozens more Japanese women to fly to the British colony. Another woman, 24-year-old <PERSON> Reiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mimura </PERSON>, moved here from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in 1984 to be closer to her idol. `` I just looked at him and felt very nervous. He was nice and gave me his records with his autograph,'' she recalled of a meeting two years ago. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON>, a muscular 5-foot-10, said he does not dare have a lover or a wife for fear of driving his fans to despair. Two girls reportedly tried to kill themselves over the actor. But despite his wild popularity in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, his efforts to impress <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> moviegoers have been disappointing. He has appeared in five American movies, including `` Battle Creek Brawl'' and `` The Cannonball Run.'' <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> was not happy with the movies, and said he would like to do a film with <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> _ free of charge if necessary. `` I need an opportunity _ a great director who wants to make a movie about <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people to hire me,'' <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> said. `` The audience will want to see any film by that director, and when they happen to see me in the movie they'll say, ` Hey, this <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> is cool.''' With no offers from <LOCATION> Spielberg </LOCATION>, however, <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> plans to star in a self-directed movie in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> next year. `` If the Americans like it, OK. If not, forget it,'' he said. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> in 1954 to parents who emigrated to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> six years later. They enrolled <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> to study acting, acrobatics and martial arts. He appeared in a few films before leaving the institute to work as a stuntman. After kung fu star <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s death in 1974, director <PERSON> Lo </PERSON> <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> picked <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> as a new talent. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON>'s career was launched in the 1976 film `` New Fist of Fury'' in which he imitated <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. More than 10 similar films quickly followed, but not until the 1978 `` Drunken Monkey in a Tiger's Eye'' did <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> find his own style of action-comedy. In 1985, <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> cracked his skull in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> while shooting a scene in which he was to leap from a castle onto a tree. Instead, he fell 50 feet to the ground, fracturing his skull and driving a splinter into his brain. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> underwent brain surgery and hearing in his right ear remains impaired. `` I never thought it would happen to me,'' he said. `` While I was lying in the hospital I thought a lot and found there are many things I have not done.'' The accident was a turning point in his life. When he returned to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, he set up a charity foundation, participated in anti-drug campaigns and ran marathons for charity. `` Now I think more positively,'' he said. `` If I want to do something, I'll do it quickly. It's not that I'm afraid I may not live through tomorrow, but I do n't want to have any regrets.''
