<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Back in 1964, a man running for the White House could still bring his campaign to the people without a vast apparatus of hired image-shapers, consultants, security forces _ anxious glances at the latest quickie polls to tell him what to say. Perhaps one of the last candidates to present himself largely unencumbered was <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. An AP reporter who covered this and many another run for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> recalls how it felt in simpler times.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>'s was the last of the freestyle presidential campaigns, innocent of consultants, short on security men, played in person instead of on television _ and seldom inhibited by any real prospect of winning the White House. That made it a perfect fit for the senator from <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. The Secret Service would have cramped his style, and he undoubtedly would have fired the kind of campaign consultants who manage campaigns these days. In 1964, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> worked with people he knew and trusted, not hired hands. He said what he thought, which sometimes changed over the course of a campaign day. He was accused of shooting from the hip, but he was n't always that careful. For all that, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>'s 1964 campaign was candid, generally honest, short on rancor despite the bitterness of some of his most ardent supporters, and remarkably prophetic. Latter-day legend notwithstanding, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> dug many of his own political traps before he became a presidential candidate. His notions about selling <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> and turning Social Security into a voluntary system are samples: Both proposals were made in pieces he wrote as Mr. Conservative, not Mr. Candidate. Actually, he tempered them during the campaign, although he liked to reminisce about the blunt way he'd talked in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> about Social Security and in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> about <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>. He repeated the proposals, but he also said that he did n't believe in changing contracts like Social Security, and that, besides, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would n't let any president make that system voluntary or sell off <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>. It was a simpler time and, too briefly, a safer time. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> had been assassinated, an event that deformed the politics of 1964. But that was an aberration. Secret Service agents were not deployed around candidates until more than four years later, after <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> had fallen to assassins. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> traveled with <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Justice </PERSON>, an automobile dealer he'd met in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> motorcade, as his sole security man during the presidential primaries. Since 1968, the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> cocoon has enveloped candidates, limiting access, controlling crowds, and often keeping voters away in the name of security. Not that <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> was a glad-hander. He sometimes seemed annoyed when crowds kept him overtime. One night an unexpected crowd of supporters turned up to cheer him as his chartered plane arrived in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> snapped a demand to know who on his staff was responsible for that. `` I'm no baby-kissing, back-slapping, blintzel-eating politician,'' he said one day in <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>. That was intended as a slap at his arch rival, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>, the Eastern Republican incarnate. Rocky, of course, delighted in being all of the above. And, like any <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> politician, he knew how to say `` blintz.'' In <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, an over-zealous <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> supporter marched <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> into the Puritain Restaurant to shake hands at lunch time. The senator did n't stay long. `` If somebody walked up to me while I was eating and stuck out his hand, I'd put a hamburger in it,'' <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> said. He was a Westerner who liked guns. Security people do not like guns around their candidates. One can only speculate at the reaction had the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> been on hand when <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> decided to fire a few shots across his driveway toward <LOCATION> Scottsdale </LOCATION>, into a bullet trap he sometimes missed. He did just that one day after entertaining a group of reporters at lunch at his home. One of them liked pistols as much as the senator did, and <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> invited him to join in target practice. This proved exciting for the rest of the party, still chatting with Mrs. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> when the gunfire began, out of the front door, one room away. `` It's just <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> with his pistol,'' said <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>, thinking to calm her guests. She made him stop shooting. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> acknowledged it probably was just as well because some of his shots had strayed into the valley below, and it seemed to bother the people at the church down there. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> also liked airplanes, as pilot and as passenger. His campaign jet was named `` <PERSON> Yia </PERSON> <PERSON> Bi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kin </PERSON>,'' Navajo for House in the Sky. It was one of the first of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 jets that now are a staple of world aviation. The senator flew it, although nobody ever admitted that. He also landed it when he arrived at <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after the election. He brought it down hard and smiled knowingly when a reporter told him the third bounce landing was a nice one although the first had been rather exciting.
</TEXT>
