<TEXT>
 It was at least that exciting when the <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> charter performed the <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> Flyby early in the campaign. The 727 took off from <LOCATION> Tri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cities </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and leveled off en route to <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. Suddenly the plane turned sharply and dove at high speed. Grown pilots _ and there were a lot in the <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> entourage _ paled. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>, up front, went into the cockpit and came back smiling. The plane kept diving toward the ground then, suddenly, leveled off and blazed down the runway at control tower level. A pilot's prank. `` That was to separate the men from the boys,'' <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> said. Consistency was not a hobgoblin of the <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> campaign. One morning in <LOCATION> Laconia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, during the primary campaign, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> said he would be inclined to withdraw from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> if Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were seated. One stop later he said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must stay in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. Another stop, and he said that if the mainland Chinese supplanted the Nationalists, it would blow <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participation to pieces. Then, that evening: `` I've never said let's get out of the U.N. I do n't know how that rumor ever got started.'' At an American Legion convention in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> likened <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Izvestia </LOCATION>. Outside, he chatted with a group of reporters and took pains to tell <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohr </PERSON>, the Times reporter who covered his campaign, that it was n't personal. `` I did n't mean you, <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON>, I meant them,'' he said. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>'s partisans despised reporters, particularly Eastern reporters. A reporter for the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> arranged for two sets of press badges. One read `` Eastern Liberal Press.'' The other read `` Western Tory Press.'' The safe course was to grab one of each. The Vietnam War was taking shape during 1964 _ the purported attack on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vessels in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Tonkin </LOCATION> came in August, after <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> had been nominated. Long before that happened, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> warned that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> had the makings of the long, agonizing conflict it became. In an unlikely setting, amid acres of blossoming pear orchards in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> that spring, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> could become a far more serious conflict than <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. He said President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> should tell the nation of the peril, and of his plans for the future. At that time, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> involvement was limited to aid and advisers. Combat forces came later. Still grappling with the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> issue that fall, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> announced that if elected he would ask former President <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> to go to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and recommend future policy. It was an ironic echo of <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>'s own promise, in 1952, that if elected, he would go to <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The problem was that nobody bothered to tell <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> what <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> was about to propose. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> never liked <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, and it only heightened his frustration at the Democratic president's landslide lead, in polls borne out by the election. Besides, the Democratic president kept mousetrapping the Republican nominee. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> had voted against the Civil Rights Act of 1964. That landmark law, and the threat of a white backlash, were backdrop realities during the campaign. The senator said he did n't want them to become divisive issues. A reporter asked whether he had talked with <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> about that concern. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> had n't, but he would. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> grabbed that opening the instant he learned of it. He said he'd meet with <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> any time. They met, at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, on <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s turf and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s terms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s people then crafted a joint statement which said in effect that the president would continue to take the high road on civil rights, and the Republcan nominee had finally agreed not to make an issue of it. On election eve, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> went north to his `` good luck town,'' <LOCATION> Fredonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, on the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> border, in Indian country. He'd wound up his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> campaigns there, and it would be the last stop on his presidential campaign, too. One reporter made it his mission to record for posterity the last words spoke in the campaign. They were not memorable. They were: `` And if there are any Paiutes out there, I want to thank you, too.'' In 1964, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had seen three presidents, <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, hold office within four years. The voters were n't about to install a fourth, even had there been a Republican nominee with wider support than <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> found. <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> knew the odds when he hobbled into the campaign, his foot in a cast after one bone spur surgery. On election night, 1964, at the Camel Back Inn, <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>'s staff set up a giant blackboard to record the popular and electoral vote, state by state. From the time the first votes were counted, the <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> landslide was evident. Nobody bothered to write a number on the big blackboard. Chalk never touched it, all night long.
</TEXT>
