<FIRST>s a BC-APN--CuttingEdge Adv28-1stAdd   08-15 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Cutting Edge, Adv 28-1st Add,0680</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>ASPEN, Colo.: world, Harlem.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The conference was held among the manicured meadows of the <ORGANIZATION> Aspen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanistic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, also founded by the Paepkes. Right away, the snack bar menu revealed it was n't an ordinary convention. Forget greasy burgers and fries, this was <LOCATION> Aspen </LOCATION>, home of the too-thin, the too-rich. Here you have toubouleh sandwiches, yogurt and cucumber soup, and brie with grapes. The participants were overwhelmingly Big City Dwellers From the Coasts. Because most were designers, wardrobes ran the gamut from silks to sleaze, black to brazen, polished to punk. The crowd's differentness became a sameness Set amid wildflowers and fresh air, spectacular sunsets and snowcapped mountains, the gathering had its share of famous names. Former television talk show host <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavett </PERSON> acted as a floating moderator. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Puttnam </PERSON>, producer of 29 films, including `` Chariots of Fire'' and `` The Killing Fields,'' talked about his disagreements with the chiefs at <ORGANIZATION> Coca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> which <PERSON> Puttnam </PERSON> recently headed, and the state of movies today. `` A movie should start out attempting to be everything _ good, exciting, commercial in the best sense _ and leave an aftertaste,'' <PERSON> Puttnam </PERSON> said. `` Where we are at now is a lack of ambition in what films can do. The dream in cinema is gone. I think money corrupts the creative process. The sheer cost of making a film today takes away -LRB- creative -RRB- risk.'' <PERSON> Puttnam </PERSON>, a Briton who lives in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and now produces films for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, said unwillingness to take creative chances pervades American corporate life today. `` There is this extraordinary pressure to perform, to out-perform last year, to out-perform this year,'' said <PERSON> Puttnam </PERSON>, a fan of smaller-budget movies with unknown actors and directors. `` The reason we are chasing the Japanese is that the Japanese have this extraordinary ability to make a decision and then take a long view.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberger </PERSON>, architecture critic of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> since 1973, said that in the past few years `` there has been a tendency to believe that the most profound effect of architecture has been deciding what kind of molding to put on the $ 3 million beach house of an investment banker.'' `` Architects have become so obsessed with size, corporate power and the lushness of detail that the idea that architecture serves a social purpose has been forgotten,'' <PERSON> Goldberger </PERSON> said. Feminist <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedan </PERSON>, founder of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> and author of `` The Feminine Mystique'' and `` The Second Stage'' and now at work on `` The Fountain of Age,'' said a new feminine mystique is telling <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women to give up the social, economic and legal gains of the past two decades and `` put on the girdle again, put on the miniskirt'' and go home again. `` The answer is ` repent of your ways, of your feminist dreams, of your ideas and your aspirations ...,''' <PERSON> Friedan </PERSON> said facetiously, nearly drowned out by laughter and applause. `` This economy would really collapse if the women went home again, to say nothing of the family's economy.'' <PERSON> Friedan </PERSON> thought the nation was coming to the end of an era of devotion to greed and gave it a verbal shove: `` The nation's resources are great enough to accept public responsibility. ... If we let go unchallenged this culture of greed, of privatism, not only are the poor, the homeless, the underclass going to create -LRB- a possible -RRB- depression, the middle class, the professional class and our children, earning more than we did when we were their age, are going to have a mean life.'' So what is The Cutting Edge, and where is it? `` The cutting edge is not always where we assume it to be,'' said <ORGANIZATION> IDCA </ORGANIZATION> co-chairman <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>. `` It crops up in unpredictable places and the prognosticators have a very hard time finding it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Tad Bartimus is the AP <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> regional reporter, based in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>.
