<HEAD>Brazil's Japanese Rediscovering their Heritage</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: An accompanying story is BC-Brazil's Japanese-Successes,
b0661.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On an April day in 1908, the steamship <PERSON> Kasato </PERSON> <PERSON> Maru </PERSON> set sail from <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, with 781 Japanese peasants contracted to work on the coffee plantations of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Their plan was to come home in two to five years and start new lives with their earnings. But most stayed in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> to become the founders of what today is the world's largest Japanese community outside <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ 1,168,000 strong. They are Brazilians first, they tell you, but as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has risen in economic power and influence across the world, they are feeling the pull of the land of their ancestors: _ <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Hori </PERSON>, 20, wearing faded blue jeans and a white sweat shirt, kneels silently on a straw mat, his eyes riveted on the kimono-clad instructor who patiently goes through the precise movements of the `` chado,'' centuries-old Japanese tea ceremony _ A few blocks away in downtown <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hifumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Konno </PERSON>, 55, in a blue and white cotton kimono, rehearses the delicate and intricate steps of the `` <PERSON> Kyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fujima </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryo </PERSON>,'' one of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s traditional classical dance forms The renewed interest in homeland traditions is a relatively recent phenomenon among <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s Japanese, according to <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanada </PERSON>, executive secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Brazil-Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>. `` For many years, especially after <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s defeat in World War II, the main concern in the community was to integrate, to be as Brazilian as possible. This led to an almost total rejection of anything identified with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' he said in an interview. `` But in the 1970s, as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> prospered, many in the community started feeling a strong sense of curiosity and a need to understand and recover a cultural past which for years had been ignored.'' He added that over the past 10 years the number of people learning Japanese at the Cultural Alliance `` has been increasing by 15 percent annually.'' The alliance houses <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s largest Japanese-language school, with more than 2,000 students. Similar increases have been registered in courses of traditional Japanese art forms such as flower arrangements, origami -LRB- paper folding -RRB- and caligraphy, he said. <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Hori </PERSON> explained why he decided to learn the tea ceremony and take Japanese language classes. `` I always felt that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s recovery after the war and its current economic strength could best be understood by studying its culture, something I knew nothing about,'' he said. <PERSON> Kaesundri </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakisaka </PERSON>, one the directors of the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese-Brazilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said another important reason for the community's renewed interest in its cultural background is `` a kind of instinctive concern that one day these traditions may disappear. During a break in her dance rehearsals, Mrs. <PERSON> Konno </PERSON> said, `` If we do n't learn and transmit our cultural heritage to the younger generations, it will all fade away.'' She said that despite her efforts, her two daughters have shown little interest `` in following my example. They have become too Brazilian.'' <PERSON> Wakisaka </PERSON> said the Japanese community's assimilation into Brazilian culture and society was `` progressing so smoothly and steadily that in 50 years it will be almost impossible to distinguish it as an ethnically different group.'' He said the main reason was growing number of interracial marriages. <PERSON> Wakisaka </PERSON> estimated there were about 115,00 marriages in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> between the descendants of Japanese and non-Japanese. Most Japanese-Brazilians interviewed insisted that their life styles and way of thinking are Brazilian, but they make clear their heritage is not far behind. <PERSON> Kenichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamai </PERSON>, a 58-year-old attorney said, `` I am so Brazilian that I only remember my Japanese background when I look at myself in the mirror.'' But, sitting on a beige sofa in his three bedroom apartment, he said he never misses a chapter of `` Takeda Shigen'' -LRB- The Great Samurai -RRB-, a soap opera produced in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and aired every Sunday in Japanese by a local TV station. He also starts his day reading <ORGANIZATION> Sao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paulo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION>, one of three Japanese-language newspapers published in <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>. With his wife <PERSON> Emi </PERSON> sitting at his side, <PERSON> Yamai </PERSON> also said he insisted that his daughter <PERSON> Regina </PERSON>, a 28-year-old dentist, `` marry a Japanese because mixed marriages never work out. And when my two sons are ready to marry, I will make the same demand.'' <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakayashi </PERSON>, a 43-year-old economist, said, `` No matter how Brazilian we feel or act or are seen by others, there is no denying our heritage. It's in our blood and will never go away.'' For <PERSON> Harumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kawasaki </PERSON>, a 50-year-old teacher in a Japanese language school, `` being Japanese in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is like having a split personality, for we are constantly straddling two entirely different cultures.''
</TEXT>
