 After pouring a cup of Japanese tea and turning down the music of Brazilian pop singer <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Nascimento </PERSON> on the stereo, <PERSON> Tania </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamura </PERSON> <PERSON> Delmanto </PERSON> said re are brief sketches of some of the Japanese who made a success in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> MANABUA </LOCATION> <LOCATION> MABE </LOCATION>, artist _ Born in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1924, <PERSON> Mabe </PERSON> immigrated to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> with his parents in 1935. After 10 years of picking coffee beans, he started painting figurative art but soon moved to abstractionist paintings. His first public recognition as an artist came in 1957 when he won the Best National Painter Award at the <ORGANIZATION> Sao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paulo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bienal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exhibition </ORGANIZATION>. Two years later he was awarded the Best Foreign Painter Award at the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Bienal Art Show. <PERSON> Mabe </PERSON> has a studio in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> but continues to paint at his home in <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>, exhibiting his work in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and abroad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> TOMIE </PERSON> <PERSON> OHTAKE </PERSON>, artist _ Born in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1914, she came to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in 1936 to visit relatives but decided to stay after the Sino-Japanese War broke out in 1937 and falling in love with agronomist <PERSON> Ruy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohtake </PERSON>, whom she married. She started painting as a hobby, but friends and relatives insisted she go public and in 1957 she exhibited her work at <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>'s Museum of Modern Art. In September she will have a one-woman show in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ one of many countries where her paintings can be found.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> FUJIO </LOCATION> <LOCATION> TACHIBANA </LOCATION>, banker _ He came to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> as a 20-year-old in 1932 to work on a coffee plantation. Because of his training as an accountant, he landed a job in 1938 with the <ORGANIZATION> Bratac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> that two years later became the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> do Sul Bank, one of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s largest. He became president in 1978 and still holds that prestigious position.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> HIRO </ORGANIZATION> HI <LOCATION> URUSHIMA </LOCATION>, entrepreneur _ He was 11 years old when he arrived in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> with his parents and seven brothers in 1936. Like most other Japanese immigrants, he worked on a coffee plantation. But in 1938 his family left the plantation and <PERSON> Urushima </PERSON> went to work in a radio repair shop in the city of <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>. In the 1940s he started his own business building transformers and radio receivers. In 1954 he began building car radios and selling them to stores and individuals. Nine years later he founded <ORGANIZATION> Motoradio </ORGANIZATION>, which today employs more than 2,000 workers at three different factories making table and car radios as well as a wide variety of electronic components.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> ANTONIO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> UENO </ORGANIZATION>, congressman _ The 65-year-old <PERSON> Ueno </PERSON> is one of three congressmen of <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> descent re-writing <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s constitution in <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>, the national capital. Born in 1923 in the southern state of <LOCATION> Parana </LOCATION>, he spent his childhood helping his parents pick coffee and cotton on local plantations. But they insisted he go to school and in 1953 he graduated college with a degree in economics. He entered politics as a councilman in the small town of <LOCATION> Assai </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Parana </LOCATION>. In 1965 he got a law degree and two years later was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brasil </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He has been a congressman ever since. He presented 134 bills for the new constitution and 34 of which have been approved, most favoring foreign capital investments in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
