<HEAD>In Complex Medical Cases, Ethics Comes To Forefront</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARK RIDGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Questions surrounding withholding and cost of treatment, and even confidentiality, have hospitals turning more frequently to special consultants and committees to help search for the answers. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> estimates that at least 60 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hospitals with 200 or more beds have such committees, made up of doctors, philosophers, theologians and social workers. A report in last week's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said 30 percent of 280 patients in a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> study presented ethical problems. Some hospitals, like <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, have doctors like <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Puma </PERSON> as consultants. La <ORGANIZATION> Puma </ORGANIZATION> does at least two consultations a week. An ethics consultant helps clarify issues and `` provides a lot of comfort for myself as a primary care physician,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, director of research and family practice at Lutheran General. In addition to medicine's capacity to prolong life, `` in a society where lawsuits are common, lawsuits are less likely when an ethics committee has been consulted,'' said Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Loma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bioethics </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` It's harder to demonstrate that a doctor has acted unprofessionally.'' The fact that not all ethics consultants are doctors raises other issues. Among them, said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>, are `` Who should be entitled to do this and what qualifications and training should they have? What are the proper duties to give to someone who is an ethics consultant _ teaching, troubleshooting, or policy-making? What is the job?'' Another unresolved issue is consultants' legal responsibility, said <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>. `` I think, down the road, the courts are going to have to clarify their role.'' Medical guidelines will ease debate over withholding treatment, said <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Puma </ORGANIZATION>. `` The big ethical issue of the 1990s is going to be medical indigents, and what kind of care we provide for patients who can not provide for themselves.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Cornell Ornithology Center Is Nest Of Information For Birders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some professional birdwatchers look down on amateurs, but the legacy of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s first ornithology professor unites their work. <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ornithology </ORGANIZATION>, which owes its creation to <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, contains millions of pages of behavior studies and photographs and the world's largest collection of birdsongs _ more than 5,000 species. Equally important, it links ornithologists and amateur birdwatchers. `` The game is to position the laboratory between the professional community and the birding community, the amateur and the professional,'' said executive director <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Walcott </PERSON>. `` We are an information broker between the two.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, an expert on red-winged blackbirds and pioneer in recording and filming wild birds, headed <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s only doctoral program in ornithology from the 1920s to the'40s. <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON>, a business graduate and student of <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s, financed much of the lab and 180-acre sanctuary near <LOCATION> Ithaca </LOCATION>. The laboratory generates money through dues and project fees, sale of publications and bird recordings, and home-study courses in ornithology and bird photography. Its 1-year-old Project FeederWatch last year paid 4,000 birdwatchers to fill out a computerized form twice weekly recording the species that appear at their backyard feeders. The goal this year is 10,000. `` We can only begin to guess at what we might have been able to accomplish if we had had this kind of information years ago,'' <PERSON> Walcott </PERSON> said, `` how many extinct species we could have saved.''
</TEXT>
