 An 11 -LCB- - foot-wide honeycombed piece of glass made with a new casting process has been sent off for a year of grinding and polishing into a mirror officials hope will lead to cheaper, more powerful telescopes The last molding material was flushed off the glass blank with a high-pressure water hose on Aug. 11, and <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON> said, `` It's a perfect piece of glass. Astronomers unveiled the blank in June when they removed the lid of a its furnace after letting it cool for weeks after it was spun-cast centrifugally in a new process that creates a lighter, more deeply curved mirror. `` This first one has been a great success,'' <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON> said. Grinding and polishing will take about a year, then the mirror will go into the Apache Point Observatory planned for the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> near Sunspot, N.M. It will be operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Astrophysical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consortium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> State universities. Work already has begun at the <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> here on a second blank, identical to the first, for another consortium. Once that blank is completed, the furnace is to be expanded for casting of a nearly 21 -LCB- - foot blank to upgrade the Multiple Mirror Telescope on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION> south of <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>
