<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 18, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Cornell Ornithology Center Is Nest Of Information For Birders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some professional birdwatchers look down on amateurs, but the legacy of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s first ornithology professor unites their work. <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ornithology </ORGANIZATION>, which owes its creation to <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, contains millions of pages of behavior studies and photographs and the world's largest collection of birdsongs _ more than 5,000 species. Equally important, it links ornithologists and amateur birdwatchers. `` The game is to position the laboratory between the professional community and the birding community, the amateur and the professional,'' said executive director <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Walcott </PERSON>. `` We are an information broker between the two.'' `` <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> is synonomous with ornithology in the minds of birdwatchers,'' said <PERSON> Elsa </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, co-publisher of Birdwatchers Digest. `` They are greatly respected as a technical and research facility. `` But <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> has also managed to serve as a popular outreach, helping bridge the gap between professional and amateur.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, an expert on red-winged blackbirds and pioneer in recording and filming wild birds, headed <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s only doctoral program in ornithology from the 1920s to the'40s. He fashioned a first-rate program at <LOCATION> Cornell </LOCATION>. But it was <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON>, a business graduate, who helped make the lab in <LOCATION> Sapsucker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Woods </LOCATION>, a 180-acre sanctuary outside <LOCATION> Ithaca </LOCATION>, a reality. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON>, who won a `` Life'' magazine contest with the bird photography <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> taught him, financed much of the construction. The main building holds the largest collection of works by bird artist <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Agassiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuertes </PERSON>. A floor-to-ceiling window overlooks a 10-acre pond, so visitors can watch feeder birds and waterfowl and listen to sounds piped in by microphones installed outside. During <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s lifetime _ he died in 1964 _ the laboratory gained international recognition, but his continued connections with amateurs and volunteer conservationists were frowned upon by the new breed of professional ornithologists. In response, the university made the lab a separate department, but without professors or course offerings and with no students of its own. It was expected to support itself financially, and generates money through dues and project fees, sale of publications and bird recordings, and home-study courses in ornithology and bird photography. Membership dropped so low by 1980 that <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> seriously considered shutting down the lab. <PERSON> Walcott </PERSON>, who earned a reputation as an educational promoter developing public television science shows like `` Nova'' and `` 3-2-1 Contact,'' has boosted its membership from 2,000 to 13,000 in eight years and rejuventated its home-study enrollment to about 9,000. `` Now that we have become stable again we are turning our attention to our research efforts and producing a tremendous scientific archive,'' he said. `` Of course, all we do here has really one focus _ conservation. The information we collect is highly useful as an environmental monitoring tool and we hope will serve as a biological early warning system.'' Its foremost study is in bioacoustics, or bird communication. `` With the help of computers we are making progress in finding out what birds say to each other, and they do communicate,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, head of the program. The research has led to similar efforts involving whales and elephants. The lab's 1-year-old Project FeederWatch last year paid 4,000 backyard birdwatchers to fill out a computerized form twice weekly recording the species that appear at their feeders. The goal this year is 10,000, and <PERSON> Walcott </PERSON> notes there are more than 82 million Americans who put out food for wild birds. `` We can only begin to guess at what we might have been able to accomplish if we had had this kind of information years ago,'' he said, `` how many extinct species we could have saved.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 18</NOTE>
