<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Stocks Edge Upward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar eased today and share prices firmed in extremely thin trading as a summer <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> holiday and the expected announcement of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures kept investors out of the stock markets. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained 48.53 points Friday, edged up 67.78 points or 0.24 percent today to close at 27,901.29. Volume on the first section was 230 million shares, the lowest full-day level this year. Until today, the lowest volume of the year was 380 million shares on Jan. 11. `` Nearly the whole exchange is on vacation and hardly anyone is selling their shares,'' said a securities dealer at a major firm, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Even less than nothing is going on,'' said another. Many non-financial businesses were closed for Obon, an annual holiday period during which Japanese honor their ancestors. Dealers also said investors were waiting on the sidelines for the expected announcement Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for June. On the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 132.95 yen, down 0.10 yen from its close Friday. It ranged from a low of 132.65 yen and a high of 133.05.
