 <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> will move closer to full economic union Friday with the signing of an agreement designed to end all trade barriers within five years. Prime Minister <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, who arrived in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> for a weeklong visit today, also has suggested the integration of the two nations' naval forces. `` Strategic logic points us in the direction of a combined ... fleet,'' he was quoted as saying Sunday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. But he was quoted as saying political union between the two <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> neighbors was unlikely. <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> will sign the Closer Economic Relations agreement in <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION> on Friday. The new agreement will end all trade barriers and unify business law and customs procedures by 1993. It also calls for greater controls on illegal immigration and drug trafficking. Since the first Closer Economic Relations agreement in 1983 relaxed tariff barriers, trade between the two countries has doubled. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s third largest market with exports valued at $ 1.68 billion. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'s second largest market with exports of $ 1.2 billion. <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> has said the new <LOCATION> Australian-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> market would not be as restrictive a trading bloc as the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>.
