<DATELINE>MODENA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Enzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrari </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s greatest sports car builder and racing pioneer, died at his home in <LOCATION> Modena </LOCATION>, his auto company announced today. He was 90. In a statement, the company said, `` <PERSON> Enzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrari </PERSON> serenely ended his earthly life Sunday, Aug. 14.'' No cause of death was given, but <PERSON> Ferrari </PERSON> was known to suffer from a kidney disease. At <ORGANIZATION> Ferrari </ORGANIZATION>'s side when he died were his son <PERSON> Piero </PERSON> and <PERSON> Piero </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Floriana </PERSON>, the statement said <PERSON> Piero </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Lina </PERSON>, who was not <ORGANIZATION> Ferrari </ORGANIZATION>'s wife, was also at the deathbed. His wife had died in 1978. At <ORGANIZATION> Ferrari </ORGANIZATION>'s request, the announcement of his death was made after the private funeral rites and burial today in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cataldo </LOCATION>, near this northern city, according to the <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> news agency. The founder and chairman of the company that bears his name and makes luxury sports cars and Formula One racers once dreamed of becoming an opera star or a sportswriter. But his first love was automobiles, and his drivers whipped the prancing black horse that decorates his bright red racing cars to victory on every major track in the world. `` It's true that I have never met any man whom I thought altogether resembled me _ but only because my faults are so enormous,'' he wrote in his autobiography. `` I have yet to meet anyone quite so stubborn as myself and animated by this overpowering passion that leaves me no time for thought or anything else. I have in fact no interest in life outside racing cars,'' he wrote. `` I have never gone on a real trip, never taken a holiday. The best holiday for me is spent in my workshops when nearly everybody else is on vacation.'' His factory, in the town of <LOCATION> Maranello </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Modena </LOCATION>, turns out about 1,300 cars a year. Hundreds of customers, book the Ferrari models years in advance and pay as much as $ 150,000, and more, for the cars. Born in February 1898, <ORGANIZATION> Ferrari </ORGANIZATION> entered motor racing in 1919 and drove with the <ORGANIZATION> Alfa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Romeo </ORGANIZATION> team for 11 years. But he never became a great driver because of a fatal flaw _ he could not bear to ruin an engine to win a race. <PERSON> Ferrari </PERSON> founded his Maranello auto works in 1946, letting other men win races in cars he produced. At the time, about 400 workers toiled painstakingly on the silvery engines. Some crankshafts were sculpted by hand out of steel, each requiring more than 80 hours of work. His drivers drove the racers to more than 4,000 victories and the <ORGANIZATION> Ferrari </ORGANIZATION> team picked up 13 world titles, including nine in the Formula One category since 1952. <PERSON> Ferrari </PERSON> was forced to reduce his business activities in February when he developed influenza. Last month, a company spokesman confirmed that <PERSON> Ferrari </PERSON> was being treated at home for kidney troubles and `` for ailments typical of his age.'' <PERSON> Ferrari </PERSON> was an avowed agnostic who made no secret of his aversion for the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION>, which had criticized him for his stoic attitude toward the deaths of his drivers in fiery accidents on the track. However, in June, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> toured the company's plant, took a spin in one of the sports cars and spoke by phone for five minutes with the bed-ridden Ferrari.
