<HEAD>Hearings Open on Harvard-Union Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Proceedings expected to begin by noon EDT; lead prospects
unlikely; also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Months after white collar workers at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> voted to unionize, a tense labor battle continues, with the <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> school being accused of union-busting as its seeks to throw out the vote. A National Labor Relations Board administrative law judge was scheduled to open hearings today on <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s challenge of the May 17 vote that created a 3,300-member union. The hearings are expected to take two weeks. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> alleges that organizers used illegal tactics, including intimidation of opponents and electioneering at the polls, to win the election by 44 votes, 1,530 to 1,486. The university wants the agency to invalidate the election. Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clerical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> deny the charges. `` What's really going on here is we beat them, and they know it, and everybody knows it,'' said <PERSON> Kristine </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rondeau </PERSON>, an organizer. `` Our union is now a permanent part of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and the only remaining question is, what's the future relationship going to be _ peace or war? <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s got to decide,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, who coordinated the university's response to the union, conceded that the school `` is in a difficult position'' because `` it's a liberal institution'' and `` the administration of the university is not reflexively anti-union and would not like to be thought of as reflexively anti-union.'' <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmetz </PERSON>, an administrative law judge from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, who is conducting the hearings, is not likely to reach a decision until mid-autumn, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, supervisory examiner in the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> office. The union drive, which began in 1975, was closely watched by national labor leaders as a bellwether for organizing white-collar workers. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said administrators believe there is `` strong evidence'' that union organizers acted improperly during the election. She said the violations include `` the union's maintenance of lists on which they checked off voters, their interrogation of voters as to how they voted, the escorting of voters to the polls, electioneering on the way to the polls and at the polls, and the providing of things of value _ such as medical care and plane fares _ to get union supporters to vote.'' <PERSON> Rondeau </PERSON> said the union conducted a legitimate get-out-the-vote operation, and nothing more. `` They're saying we were at the polls keeping lists, and we were not,'' she said. `` They're saying we were intimidating people. That's incredible, no matter how much you stretch it.''
