<HEAD>Peasants Raid Forest, Cut Down Trees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Peasants in southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have cut down and stolen more than 10,000 trees from a state-run forest since the beginning of the year, an official newspaper said. The Legal Daily said Monday that illegal logging has been increasing at the <LOCATION> Wugong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> forest in <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION> province because forestry officials refuse to punish the peasants. The report said in the past peasants used to sneak up the mountain and cut one or two trees down. Now, it said, `` they steal dozens of trees and even hundreds of trees at a time.'' The peasants use the wood to build houses and for fuel. On April 19, the paper said, 2,000 peasants from a nearby village looted more than 200 cubic yards of trees. Five days later, peasants again entered the forest and cut down trees. This time forestry guards were injured, the paper said. The report said the <LOCATION> Wugong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> forest has 49,444 acres of trees and is one of the country's main producers of wood products. The Chinese press has said that illegal logging poses serious problems for the environment and the development of agriculture. Illegal logging quickens soil erosion and creates conditions where small amounts of rain can cause major floods. Last year, 247,100 acres of forests in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were destroyed by illegal logging and 91 million yuan, or about $ 24.5 million, in trees were stolen, the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily reported in March. Monday's report said the problem could not be solved in <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION> province because officials there are too lenient.
