<HEAD>Peabody Coal lays off 128 workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRVIEW HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has laid off 128 more employees from one of its operations in this <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clair </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> community, reducing the company's work force to only 32. Of the 128 workers laid off Friday, 50 were laid off indefinitely, while the 78 others were offered new jobs or transfers to other Peabody operations. The layoffs bring to 540 the number of local workers eliminated in the past three years. <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION>, a wholly owned subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, operates 40 surface and underground mines in nine states. Another 85 administrative and clerical workers throughout the company were also laid off. The latest layoffs occurred because of a reduced demand for high-sulfur <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> coal, said company spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenfield </PERSON>. Large users of coal have continued to switch to other forms of energy such as nuclear energy or use lower-sulfur coal from western or eastern states, he said. `` We have reduced the number of employees at the mine level over the past several years in response to the highly competitive market for coal,'' company president <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said Friday in a statement. `` The layoffs bring our support staff more in line with the current active mining employee levels within these operations,'' he said. Further layoffs will depend on government regulation, <PERSON> Greenfield </PERSON> said. High-sulfur coal contributes pollutants to the air that need to be reduced in order to comply with federal clean air legislation, he said. `` Further tightening of clean-air legislation will not help,'' <PERSON> Greenfield </PERSON> said. In October 1985, <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> laid off 100 management employees at what was then its <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> headquarters and 70 people in its <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Division, which includes the <LOCATION> Fairview </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> office. The company's headquarters was moved in April 1986 to <LOCATION> Henderson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>. A total of 151 miners were laid off at two Belleville-area mines in 1987 The company's Illinois Division office is responsible for seven mines _ six in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, with four in the <LOCATION> Belleville </LOCATION> area, and one in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. At the end of 1987, those mines employed 2,844 and produced 10.8 million tons of coal, <PERSON> Greenfield </PERSON> said. That was down from 4,890 employees and coal production of 16 million tons of coal from 15 mines three years ago.
