<HEAD>Judge Orders Publishers To Pay Legal Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INEZ, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The co-publishers of the <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercury </ORGANIZATION> have been ordered to pay the court costs incurred by their rival legal newspaper in a dispute over circulation. Attorneys <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stayton </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Inez </PERSON>, have been ordered to pay legal expenses exceeding $ 11,000 for <PERSON> Homer </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcum </PERSON>, publisher of the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Countian </PERSON>. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Paintsville </LOCATION> also ruled that they must pay <PERSON> Marcum </PERSON>'s costs if they appeal the order. <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> said they must pay the legal bills because they continued to press the circulation case after it was settled in March, 1987. <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stayton </PERSON> are the Mercury's co-publishers. `` The continued litigation as set forth can only lead this court to believe that counsel for the Mercury caused the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Countian </PERSON> to incur additional legal expenses for no valid reason other than to harass the plaintiff,'' <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> said Friday in his 39-page decision. The decision was the result of a hearing held last December. The case began in February, 1987, when <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiscal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> voted to designate the Mercury as the county's legal newspaper based on figures presented by that newspaper. The move took the county's legal business away from <PERSON> Marcum </PERSON>'s feisty <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Countian </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcum </PERSON> called <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>'s circulation figures `` bogus'' and sued the next day. In his ruling, <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> said that the Mercury's press run of 2,800 included hundreds of papers given away free in <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>'s law offices in <LOCATION> Prestonsburg </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hindman </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Countian </PERSON>'s circulation is about 4,350, <PERSON> Marcum </PERSON> said. On March 13, 1987, fiscal court voted 5-0 to reinstate the <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Countian </PERSON> as the legal newspaper. <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> ruled that even though the circulation dispute was settled when the magistrates reversed their decision, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stayton </PERSON> continued to press the case, forcing <PERSON> Marcum </PERSON> to incur additional legal costs for depositions and responding to motions. <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> invoked a civil judicial procedure rule requiring attorneys who file so-called frivolous lawsuits or motions to pay for defendants' legal expenses.
