<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Britain's Cured Economy is Suffering Something of a Relapse</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Britain-Unemployment</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just a few months ago, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s economic `` disease'' of rampant inflation, sky-high interest rates and persistent unemployment was pronounced cured y just about everyone except the Conservative government's staunchest critics. Today, the economy is suffering something of a relapse, exhibiting that old familiar symptom, higher inflation, and the government admits it is troubling. In addition, a hike in interest rates and a sharp widening of the trade deficit are worrying economists. Ironically, the symptoms' cause is the economy's vigorous growth, which is stretching resources and driving up prices. Like its trading ally, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> faces the threat that its economy could overheat into recession. The peak came in March when the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s top official, Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, announced the first surplus budget in nearly 20 years and slashed the top income tax rate to 40 percent from 60 percent. Since then, the attention has turned instead to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s annual inflation rate, which, fed by strong consumer spending, has jumped from 3.5 percent to 4.6 percent in June. In his budget speech, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> had forecast an inflation rate of 4 percent by the end of the year. To combat higher inflation _ Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s No 1 economic priority _ the government has pushed interest rates up more than 3 percentage points since early June. `` Whatever action is necessary to keep inflation under control, this government will take,'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> told members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in late July, characterizing the pickup as `` modest but unacceptable.'' Strength in the dollar gave the government room to raise interest rates without pushing the British pound dangerously high. But the pound, which has been trading at about 3.20 West German marks, remains well above a rate of 3 marks which the government long had protected. The pound broke through that ceiling in March, raising concerns that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s export competitiveness might be hurt. Indeed, the trade deficit is much worse than <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> had forecast. For the first six months of 1988, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had a current account deficit of 5.6 billion pounds -LRB- $ 9.6 billion -RRB-, compared with a 1.6 billion pound -LRB- $ 2.6 billion -RRB- deficit in all of 1987. The current account includes `` invisible'' trade such as services and overseas investment earnings. In his budget speech, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> had forecast a trade deficit of 4 billion pounds -LRB- $ 7 billion -RRB- for all of 1988. `` Things have deteriorated,'' said <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Harwood </PERSON>, an economist at the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Warburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` The major part of the reason for the deterioration has been the way the economy has been growing so much faster than expected.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, an economist with the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grieveson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said `` domestic demand is just growing too quickly for its own good.'' The latest survey conducted by the polling organization Market and <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, showed that in July, for the first time since February 1987, more people thought the state of the economy would get worse rather than better over the next year. Economists expect <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s gross domestic product _ its total output of goods and services _ to grow between 3.5 percent and 4 percent this year, faster than the 3 percent forecast by <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> in March, and following growth of 4.4 percent in 1987. On top of the troubling symptoms, there have been recurrent reports of a rift between Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> over currency exchange policy. These have been fueled by the pound's rise and the government's negotiations with Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s former economic adviser, Sir <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, for him to return to her Downing Street office next year Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> advocates free-market policies while <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> favors managing exchange rates through direct intervention in the markets and the adjustment of interest rates. However, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> survived a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> reshuffle by Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> in late July and now appears likely to remain until at least after next spring's budget. But the economic outlook remains worrying, <PERSON> Harwood </PERSON> said. Inflation will peak at 6 percent early next year, interest rates might move higher into the double digits, and the trade deficit probably will balloon to 10 billion pounds -LRB- $ 17.2 billion -RRB- in 1988, <PERSON> Harwood </PERSON> predicted. The government remains upbeat. `` The difficulties that beset us are difficulties we have successfully dealt with in the past, and will do so again, without drama, and without interrupting the steady progress we have already achieved,'' <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
