<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rate Has Fallen For Two Years, But Critics Claim It Is Massaged</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thanks to a strong economy, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s persistently high unemployment rate has fallen sharply, but critics claim the government is massaging the figures to make them ook even better than they are. Opponents of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government agree that unemployment is down, but say exaggeration in the degree of improvement is encouraging apathy toward the unemployed. The jobless rate has been falling for two years, reaching 8.4 percent in June, its lowest point in nearly seven years, the Department of Employment says. Unemployment has fallen to 2.38 million people from a peak of 11.5 percent, or about 3.31 million in June 1986. The decline is the fastest among major Western industrialized nations, the government says. But the Unemployment Unit, a private research and lobby organization, says the rate would be 10.6 percent, representing 3.03 million people, if the calculation method were the same as when the Conservatives first came into power in 1979. The British figures compare with a West German rate of 8.9 percent in June, which is unchanged from two years earlier, and a French rate of 10.9 percent in May, which is up from 10.7 percent two years before. An <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who requested anonymity, said: `` We're still reasonably confident that it -LRB- ours -RRB- is an accurate measure of unemployment.'' Lawmaker <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Meacher </PERSON>, the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s spokesman on unemployment, said: `` Unemployment has indeed been going down over the last two years, but only about half as fast as the government has been claiming.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>, a columnist for the Independent newspaper, wrote: `` If ... the calculations were done differently, it is doubtful whether the government could claim, or would receive, anything like the credit that the media and the public now bestow upon it.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Convery </PERSON>, a director of the Unemployment Unit, said Britons have become `` a little bit anesthetized,'' partly because they generally are feeling better off economically, and partly because the government has scored `` several sizable propaganda victories.'' National unemployment registers have been the source for unemployment statistics in all Common Market countries except <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, the Unemployment Unit said. In 1982, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> alone began basing its unemployment rate on the number claiming unemployment benefits, rather than the number registered as unemployed, it said. Since 1979, the government has made 22 changes in the way it measures joblessness, all except one of which have reduced the official unemployment rate, the Unemployment Unit said. The government denies that it has made that many changes or that its alterations are designed to make the numbers look better. In a recent monthly unemployment report, the government said it began counting as employed those people who are in government training programs. That reduced the unemployment rate by 0.1 percent. The unit said the government has removed from the unemployment benefit lists jobless men over age 60 who receive other kinds of benefits. Part-time workers, whose numbers are increasing, have always been counted as employed, and many jobless married women are n't eligible for unemployment benefits, it said Another way of measuring unemployment is to conduct surveys which ask adults questions about their employment status. This method is used monthly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the government uses the method once a year, and reveals the results a year later. By the survey method, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had an unemployment rate of 10.7 percent in the spring of 1987. By the government's regular method, the rate was 10.8 percent. `` They are so close that it shows that our own measure is accurate,'' the department spokesman said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 20-21</NOTE>
