<SECOND>BC-Germany-Meat Scandal,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hormone Scandal Involving Calf Breeders Grips West Germany, Could
Reach Netherlands and Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German scandal involving the use of illegal hormones to spur the growth of calves may spread to the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, officials and news reports said Monday. Discovery of the illegal hormone use has led to charges of an international `` hormone mafia'' and the arrest of a major veal producer in northwestern <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` There is an illegal market for animal drugs that is causing mischief both within the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and outside of it,'' said <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthiesen </PERSON>, agriculture minister for <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rhine-Westphalia </LOCATION>. The main substance at issue is testosterone, the male hormone that is suspected of being a cancer-causing agent in large doses. Authorities last week arrested veal producer <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Hying </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Borken </LOCATION> in the northwestern part of the country after discovering illegal hormone use. <PERSON> Hying </PERSON> was arrested on criminal charges of violating the country's food and health laws that ban the use of hormones. Prosecutors say <PERSON> Bernhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wigger </PERSON>, another veal producer from the same area, is suspected of using similar banned substances. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rentmeister </PERSON>, a spokesman for the city of <LOCATION> Borken </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Wigger </PERSON> kept `` a thousand or more calves'' in the nearby <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Martsch </PERSON>, a spokesman for the environmentalist Greens party in the affected state of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rhine-Westphalia </LOCATION>, said: `` There is a possibility Wigger had business dealings with <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>.'' He did not reveal further details during a press conference in <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION>. The Hamburg-based <ORGANIZATION> Der </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spiegel </ORGANIZATION> magazine and the <ORGANIZATION> Westdeutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rundfunk </ORGANIZATION> radio station of <LOCATION> Cologne </LOCATION> said the hormones themselves came from the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. Officials say they fear the scandal will grow. <PERSON> Matthiesen </PERSON> told reporters on Sunday he is convinced there is an `` international hormone mafia'' behind the illegal use. `` We have had many, many indications, not only in the last few days but also for several months, that confirm this view,'' the state minister said. `` There are ties going beyond national boundaries.'' West German offficials say it's the largest hormone scandal in the country's nearly 40-year history. The issue is particularly sensitive for West Germans, who are wary of food additives and similar substances. Health food firms also have been experiencing sharp growth in recent years, while news accounts still chronicle the lingering effects of the 1986 <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident on the nation's food supply. <PERSON> Matthiesen </PERSON> on Friday ordered the confiscation of about 14,000 calves belonging to Wigger because of the suspected use of testosterone. Testosterone is the principal male sex hormone, and it is responsible for various male sex characteristics. Its use is banned throughout the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wigger </PERSON> says that needle marks found on a sampling of his calves were only for routine immunizations. Also last week, in a separate action, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rhine-Westphalia </LOCATION> officials accused calf breeder Hying of using testosterone on thousands of his calves. Officials ordered the slaughter of 4,200 of <PERSON> Hying </PERSON>'s calves that tested postive for the hormone. More than 10,000 others were also being tested. Hying remained in jail Monday afternoon pending further investigation. Local prosecutor <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Deupmann </PERSON> told reporters Sunday that 500 of the calves remained unaccounted for after several days of investigations. `` We ca n't exclude the possibility that these calves have already been slaughtered, prepared and have reached the markets,'' <PERSON> Deupmann </PERSON> added. Both Wigger and Hying have their businesses in towns located less than 10 kilometers -LRB- six miles -RRB- from the Dutch border. While experts say that testosterone is a suspected cancer-causing agent, West German scientists say that quantities of the substance found in the calves pose no danger to humans.
</TEXT>
