<FIRST>r f AM-OverseasInflation     08-15 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Overseas Inflation,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>CIA Report Says Inflation Up Last Spring in US, Industrial
Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inflation, as measured by consumer prices, rose last spring in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its main trading partners, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> report made available Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Directorate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> found that while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation fell from 3.7 percent in 1987 to an annualized rate of 3.4 percent in the first quarter, it rose in the March-June period to 4.8 percent. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s inflation rate fell from a 4.4 percent rate last year to 3.2 percent in the first quarter, but also picked up in the second quarter, to 5 percent, the report said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had a 4.1 percent inflation rate in 1987. The level dropped to 2.4 percent in the first quarter and rose to 6.1 percent in the second quarter, the report said. Among other major industrialized nations tracked in the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> report, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s first-quarter inflation rate fell by 2.1 percent from a 0.1 percent rate in 1987 but rose to 2.8 percent in the second quarter. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s 1987 inflation of 0.3 percent doubled to 0.6 percent in the first quarter and rose to 1.9 percent in the spring. The rise was less marked in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, countries more usually inclined to inflation. The French rate of 2.8 percent in the second quarter of 1988 was an increase over the winter rate of 2.3 percent, but still below the 3.3 percent of 1987. In <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the rate was 4.6 percent in 1987, after falling steadily since the 14.9 percent level of 1983. It was down to 3.1 percent in the first quarter of this year but then rose again to 4.5 percent in the second three months. The <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>'s twice-monthly `` Economic and Energy Indicators'' for July 29 did not provide figures for smaller countries. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, which does, says inflation on the consumer level among 21 industrial countries rose to an annualized rate of 3 percent in May from 2.9 percent of 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> said the average inflation level for 116 other countries, mostly in the Third World, was 39.8 percent in 1987. It increased to a rate of 55.7 percent in January, however few figures for later months were available. Financial authorities have been especially worried about <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, with the biggest economy in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the biggest debt in the Third World. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> reported Brazilian inflation at more than 229 percent last year and rising at an annual rate of just under 500 percent in April. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s rate was 131 percent in 1987, having risen steadily throughout the year, according to the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>. It has been reported rising since, but the fund had no 1988 figures for <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> in its statistics for August. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, on the other hand, has been keeping its rate below 3 percent in recent years, although it reached that level in 1987 and reported an annual rate of 7.4 percent this June, the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, where the inflation rate hit a high of 11,750 percent in 1985, was down to 15 percent last year and has been reporting between 8 percent and 9 percent in 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> said. The current inflation front-runner among the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>'s members is <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, with an annual rate of more than 3,766 percent in June.
</TEXT>
