<HEAD>OPEC Head Sees 1 Million Barrel Per Day Cut After Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> General Secretary <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> said Monday the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> cease-fire should lower <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production by around 1 million barrels a day, enabling the organization to solve its overproduction problem without drastic output cuts. Oil traders reacted skeptically to the statement and oil prices were little changed. The September contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 9 cents to $ 15.61 a barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, who is touring Latin American oil producers, said he will go to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> following the scheduled Aug. 20 cease-fire to try to convince the former enemies to accept equal production quotas as they end their eight-year war. He said said the organization could opt for a new lower benchmark price `` of, say, $ 17'' in its November regular meeting as an alternative to cutting production. He added that the organization's price committee would meet sometime after the last week in August but before the Nov. 21 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministerial conference. `` The outcome of the cease-fire is anyone's guess, but my opinion is that -LRB- <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> -RRB- will be rational and what they will rationally want is higher prices to build their economies,'' <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> told a press conference. `` By bringing <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s production to equal that of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, this will reduce <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production without reducing the temporary quota of anyone -LRB- else -RRB-. ... With that policy, we will be able to strengthen prices without a lower production level,'' he said. `` I will try my best to convince <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to accept parity,'' said <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, who is the <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> oil minister. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s quota is 2,369,000 barrels per day. He said a parity agreement would `` at least'' reduce <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s production by 600,000 to 700,000 barrels per day, while an end to oil loans to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> by its allies <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> could result in a total cutback of 1 million barrels He said he would visit both nations in the last week of August and would report the results of his talks to the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> price committee, which would then meet prior to the organization's November regular conference He said <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> might decide in November for `` a higher production level but at a lower price of, say, $ 17'' per barrel. `` What strategy we take depends on the -LRB- regular -RRB- conference,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s current target price is $ 18 per barrel, although actual market prices are $ 14 to $ 15 a barrel.
