, scheduled for release by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> before the market opened Tuesday. But there was a widespread view that whatever the deficit, it was more likely to hurt stocks than help them. A number vastly higher than the $ 10.9 billion shortfall in May could weaken the dollar and encourage a selloff in stocks, some brokers argued. Conversely, a sharply lower figure could also hurt stocks by reinforcing fears that the domestic economy is growing too fast. Declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 4-to-1 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 1,194 down, 345 up and 432 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> floor totaled 128.56 million shares, down from 176.96 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 150.33 million shares. Technology and computer stocks were among the biggest losers, led by <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION>, which dropped 3 to 97, its lowest point in nearly two years. Elsewhere, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> dropped 2 ~ to 115 -LRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> dropped 1 ~ to 54 -LCB-, <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> dropped 1 to 32 \ and National Semiconductor dropped | to Among the blue chips, <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION> fell 2 to 80 -LCB-, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> fell -RCB- to 39 -LCB-, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> fell -LCB- to 35 -LCB- and <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 -LCB- to 47 -LRB-. Takeover-related activity boosted several stocks, notably <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Shoe, which jumped 5 ~ to 24 -LCB- on reports it would consider a possible sale or restructuring <ORGANIZATION> Interco