<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Soar On Hot, Dry Weather Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures posted their strongest gains in a week Monday in response to predictions that crops in the drought-weary Corn Belt would bake in triple-digit heat for most of this week. On other markets, most livestock and meat futures rose; precious metals advanced; energy futures were higher; and stock-index futures retreated. Monday's midday weather forecasts, coming on the heels of a hot, mostly dry weekend in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, stoked fears of further damage to the crops and helped push most corn, oat and soybean contracts up their permitted daily limits on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Meteorologists said the same weather pattern that had made the spring and early summer unseasonally warm and dry was reestablishing itself and intensifying, promising at least several more days of searing heat in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. `` We're going to have extreme heat right into Thursday, 100 to 110 degrees in the Corn Belt,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Notis </PERSON>, a private forecaster based in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. After the close, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issued a six-to-10-day outlook predicting above-normal temperatures but normal to above-normal rainfall for the Farm Belt during the first five days of next week. Analysts said the soybean crop was nearing the end of its vulnerable flowering and pod-setting stage, a four-to-six-week period during which weather plays a crucial role in determining yields. The hot weekend weather probably caused some deterioration of the soybean crop, analysts said. And the forecasts for similar weather this week likely means yields will fall further, making contracts for future deliveries of soybeans more precious, <PERSON> Karlin </PERSON> said. Corn and oat futures soared their 10-cents-a-bushel daily limit. Soybeans were limited to moves of 30 cents a bushel, expect for the limitless August contract, which finished with a gain of more than 38 cents. Wheat settled 9 cents to 14 -LCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.92 a bushel; corn was 7 -RCB- cents to 10 cents higher with September at $ 2.97 \ a bushel; oats were 7 -LCB- cents to 10 cents higher with September at $ 2.87 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 27 -LCB- cents to 38 -LCB- cents higher with August at $ 8.87 a bushel Livestock and meat futures finished mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly seven-state cattle-on-feed report. The government reported cattle marketings during July were 4 percent higher than the same month a year ago, which surprised most analysts and prompted predictions of a sharply higher opening Tuesday. The number of cattle on feed Aug. 1 in the seven largest cattle-producing states was 2 percent larger than a year ago, while 2 percent fewer cattle were placed on feedlots in those states during July. The high marketing number startled analysts, most of whom had expected a decline. The number meant there had been fewer drought-related sales of cattle to packing houses than analysts had believed, said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Live cattle closed .07 cent to .45 cent higher with August at 69.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to 1.15 cents higher with August at 81.75 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .57 cent higher with August at 47.37 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .52 cent lower to .70 cent higher with August at 33.65 cents a pound. Precious metals futures posted modest gains on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in response to the inflationary implications of higher prices for most other commodities, said <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Savaiko </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Gold settled $ 1.70 to $ 2 higher with August at $ 433 a troy ounce; silver was 4.5 cents to 4.6 cents higher with September at $ 6.785 a troy ounce Energy futures prices rose on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in thin dealings in the absence of major fresh news to drive the market. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 14 cents higher with September at $ 15.61 a barrel; heating oil was .23 cent to .41 cent higher with September at 44.27 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .39 cent to .75 cent higher with September at 46.37 cents a gallon. Stock-index futures slumped on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid fears of rising interest rates, analysts said. The contract for September delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 3.45 points lower at 259.10.
