<HEAD>Dollar Mixed Ahead of Trade Figures; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mixed Monday in mostly light trading, as some dealers sold the currency in anticipation of Tuesday's report on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for June. Gold prices rose. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid price for gold of $ 432.35 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $ 431 late Friday. The dollar started the trading day by falling in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, then recovering from its early lows to finish little changed in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The dollar retreated anew against several key currencies in later <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading. Analysts attributed that decline mainly to dollar sales by traders balancing their dollar-heavy positions ahead of the latest of the monthly trade reports, which tend to strongly influence the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's movements. A negative trade performance usually sends the dollar lower, and vice versa. `` We had some slight lightening of long dollar positions,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>, a vice president of corporate trading at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Traders are reluctant to hold big dollar positions because of the possibility of a surprise in the June figures. Many traders and economists are expecting a shortfall of between $ 10 billion and $ 12 billion. The trade deficit was $ 10.9 billion in May. Dealers said the dollar was supported, on the other hand, by the continuing impact of last week's unexpected hike to 6.5 percent in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s discount rate, the interest it charges on loans to member <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial institutions. Rising <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates make dollars more valuable. The dollar was scarcely affected by the news Monday that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial production shot up 0.8 percent in July, the biggest increase in nine months, market watchers said. `` All the traders are waiting for the next direction in the dollar'' from the trade figures, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON>, a dealer for <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Switzerland </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar traded at 132.95 Japanese yen, down 0.10 yen from Friday's close. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 133.15 yen. By the end of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading, the dollar was at 133.32 yen, up slightly from 133.28 yen late Friday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.7145 to buy one British pound, cheaper than $ 1.7155 late Friday. Later, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound remained steady at $ 1.7145, more expensive than $ 1.7130 late Friday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.8805 West German marks, down from 1.8833; 1.5790 Swiss francs, up from 1.5777; 6.3760 French francs, down from 6.3965; 1,394.75 Italian lire, down from 1,397.50; and 1.2270 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2111 Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday: 1.8810 West German marks, up from 1.8805; 1.5780 Swiss francs, up from 1.5750; 6.3780 French francs, down from 6.3810; 2.1257 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1146; 1,398.00 Italian lire, up from 1,395.50; and 1.2196 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2195. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 430.40 a troy ounce, compared with late Friday's bid of $ 431.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, gold fell to a bid $ 431.00 an ounce, compared with Friday's $ 432.50. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 433.80 an ounce, up from Saturday's finish of $ 430.68. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold for current delivery rose to $ 433 a troy ounce from $ 431.30 late Friday. Silver bullion prices dipped in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 6.72 a troy ounce from $ 6.73 late Friday. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver for current delivery rose to $ 6.757 a troy ounce from $ 6.712 late Friday.
