<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-FarmCredit     08-15 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Farm Credit,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Credit System Reports Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Farm Credit System on Monday reported a profit for the second quarter, continuing an improvement trend based on a reduction in its provision for loan losses. The system said it had combined net income of $ 170 million for the quarter, compared with a net loss of $ 46 million a year ago. Also contributing to the positive results were increased net interest income and a gain on the sales of certain properties. The system's net interest income totaled $ 214 million, compared with $ 110 million in the year-ago period. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fass </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the financing arm of the farm credit system, said improvements in net interest income resulted from increased reinstatements of nonaccrual loans to accrual status and from a modest decrease in the system's overall cost of debt. When loans are placed on nonaccrual status they are accounted for only as they come in rather than when they are due. During the second quarter, the system reported negative provisions for loan losses of $ 181 million, compared with a negative provision of $ 10 million a year earlier. `` In spite of the current drought, the recent improvements in the agricultural economy continued throughout the second quarter, resulting in stabilized loan collateral values and other improvements in the overall credit quality of the system's loan portfolio,'' <PERSON> Fass </PERSON> said. He noted that while it is too early to assess the impact of the current drought on system institutions, the system `` has been monitoring the drought very closely because of its potential impact on borrowers in certain parts of the country.'' For the first six months, the system reported net income of $ 336 million compared with a loss of $ 201 million a year ago. Net interest income during the period totaled $ 360 million, up from $ 258 million a year ago. During the second half, the system reported negative provisions for loan losses of $ 341 million, compared with a provision of $ 105 million a year earlier. The Farm Credit System consists of 37 borrower-owned banks and associations serving the rural economy. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> put it on a more secure footing last year by authorizing the issuance of up to $ 4 billion in government-backed, low-interest loans. The 1987 legislation, by increasing confidence in the Farm Credit System, made it possible to narrow the interest-rate spreads on Farm Credit debt obligations over <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities.
</TEXT>
