<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Some Allegations in Suits Against Media General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Monday dismissed lawsuit allegations that top <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> officials had an obligation to consider an unsolicited merger offer from investor <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> refused to throw out suit allegations that Media General made misleading statements in a recent proxy fight and that its board of directors may have acted improperly in creating a two-tiered stock structure that makes takeovers impossible without the consent of top management. The allegations were contained in two lawsuits filed by stockholders against the Richmond-based media company after <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> made a $ 1.8 billion buyout offer for the company's Class A stock in late February. Media General repeatedly rebuffed the overtures by <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, who staged an unsuccessful proxy fight for three seats on the board of directors in May. Media General Chairman <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> and his family own 71 percent of the company's Class B shares, which control the election of the other six board members. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> has said the family's interest is not for sale <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> failed in a lawsuit to get a ruling allowing a combined Class A and B shareholders' majority vote on the takeover offer, and was critical of the company's two-tier stock structure. On Monday, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> told the plaintiffs in the shareholder suits that they should be prepared to show him at a Sept. 8 pre-trial meeting that their cases should go to a jury. `` For some time now the court has suspected that both were filed with the thought in mind that if <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> was successful on his claims, the other shareholders might reap a corresponding windfall,'' the judge said. Stockholders <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> filed one of the suits, contending they paid too much for their <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> stock because the price was inflated by incomplete or misleading statements by some of the company's top officers. Ms. <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> also claimed the <ORGANIZATION> Bryans </ORGANIZATION> had a fiduciary duty to investigate and consider <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s merger plan and a later restructuring proposal. But <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> noted the <ORGANIZATION> Bryans </ORGANIZATION> also are the principal stockholders, in addition to being directors. `` Once the <ORGANIZATION> Bryans </ORGANIZATION> as controlling shareholders had firmly rejected <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s offer, the board of directors had practically no role to play with respect'' to the <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> offer, the judge said. The <ORGANIZATION> Bryans </ORGANIZATION>' duty as directors `` does not obliterate their right, as shareholders, to sell or not to sell their stock as they choose,'' said <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. The second suit was filed by <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>, who said the <ORGANIZATION> Bryans </ORGANIZATION>, as principal shareholders, had a duty to other shareholders. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> dimissed that part of <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>'s suit, saying <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law made no such requirement.
