<HEAD>Nursing Home Firm in Real Estate Deals Worth $155 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Troubled Beverly Enterprises, the nation's biggest nursing-home company, announced Monday it had arranged real estate transactions to raise $ 155 million to cover an anticipated debt. The company said it would mortgage 75 nursing homes to raise $ 120 million in cash and raise an additional $ 35 million by selling and then leasing back 27 additional facilities. Neither transaction will affect patients or staff at any of the nursing homes or congregate living centers involved, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Beverly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, suffering under heavy debt and slow reimbursements, said it would use the cash to repay $ 148 million worth of liquid yield option notes due Sept. 30. The notes, similar to zero-coupon bonds, are publicly traded. The company has arranged with a lender to take out mortgages on 75 nursing homes in 17 states that either are owned outright or carry small mortgages, said <ORGANIZATION> Beverly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. He refused to reveal the identity of the lender for the pool of mortgages. The sale-leaseback deal calls for purchase of 26 nursing homes and one congregate living center in seven states to <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> real estate investment trust. <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> announced it had agreed to pay $ 62 million for the facilities. The transaction includes assumption of $ 10 million in mortgages by <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> and for <ORGANIZATION> Beverly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterpris