<HEAD>Striking Nurses Bargaining Again, Service Workers Accept Accord</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 6-7 bgng `On wages' with two grafs to CORRECT that
only one tier of workers gets 3 percent each of two years of
contract and that bonuses are `up to' $300</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some 1,700 hospital service workers at seven hospitals overwhelmingly approved a two-year contract Monday while more than 2,000 striking nurses from six of the same hospitals returned to the bargaining table. Despite ratification, the agreement calls for members of Local 250 of the <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> to remain off the job until the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> ratifies an accord. But union leaders this weekend indicated it was not certain they would enforce that provision if the nurses' dispute continues for more than a few days. The service workers' union reported 92 percent of its members voted for ratification of a contract, which was reached in a 60-hour negotiating session under the auspices of Mayor <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnos </PERSON> and a federal mediator. The union said it struck a compromise over sick time and vacation days, and eliminated plans by the hospitals to require workers to pay a share of the basic health insurance plan. It also said the two-year agreement restored fringe benefits for both full-time and part-time workers. On wages, the licensed vocational nurses will get a 3 percent increase over two years, going from $ 12.05 an hour to $ 12.40 an hour. The technical classes will get $ 12.25 by the end of the contract. Employees at the lower end of a two-tier wage system will get 3 percent increases in each of the two years. Service and maintenance workers, who account for 45 percent of union membership, will get no raise, but lump-sum bonuses of up to $ 300 by the end of the pact. It was the first strike for Local 250 in 50 years. Talks between the Affiliated Hospitals management group and the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> were renewed Sunday, also assisted by <PERSON> Agnos </PERSON> and the mediator. The service workers accord raised hopes for a quick end to the labor problems that have hobbled eight hospitals for nearly a month. The major issues in the nurses strike, which started Aug. 2, include demands for big salary increases, overtime pay for weekend work and staffing improvements. The nurses object to a management demand for the right to impose 12-hour workdays. Local 250's members include vocational nurses, surgical and psychiatric technicians, dietary workers, janitors and housekeeping employees. Pay currently ranges from $ 7.90 an hour for lower-tier housekeeping, laundry and and food service workers and hospital aides to $ 11.90 hourly for technicians and licensed vocational nurses. Within a day of the tentative agreement, talks with the registered nurses began, but <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Agnos </PERSON>, cautioned against hopes for an immediate settlement. The average salary for a nurse working for one of the Affiliated Hospitals ranges between $ 30,072 and $ 37,692 for day shifts, and $ 34,583 to $ 43,346 for night shift nurses. Hospitals hit by the strike have employed nurses from around the country as replacements. The replacements are being recruited with promises of hourly wages ranging between $ 20 and $ 25 an hour, plus free air fare and accommodations while in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> CNA </ORGANIZATION> said the high cost of hiring replacements was applying great pressure on the hospitals to settle quickly. The Affiliated Hospitals group represents Children's, <PERSON> Marshal </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zion </LOCATION>, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Seton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Daly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Nurses also are on strike at <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where talks are being held separately. The service workers union are on strike at the same hospitals, plus <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where the registered nurses are not unionized.
