<SECOND>BC-Cabot-GAF,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeover Defense Keys on GAF's Legal Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a unique move aimed at fending off a possible hostile takeover by <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which has been indicted on charges of stock manipulation, <ORGANIZATION> Cabot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has adopted a defense designed to repel attacks by companies facing government investigation. Wayne-based <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Aug. 1 for antitrust clearance to raise its 4.9 percent stake in <LOCATION> Cabot </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Waltham </LOCATION>, Mass.-based energy and chemicals company, to as much as 25 percent. <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON> responded by amending its anti-takeover defense so it would be triggered if at least 15 percent of a company's common stock was held by a person targeted for government investigation or action. Once the `` poison pill'' was triggered, <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON> stockholders could buy more shares at half the market price, making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive. A federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> indicted <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> and its vice-chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> in July on charges they manipulated the price of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> common stock after an unsuccessful attempt to take over the larger company in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> both pleaded innocent to the charges in the indictment, which marked the first criminal charges against a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial enterprise stemming indirectly from revelations of <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the Wall Street felon at the center of the widespread insider trading scandal. The indictment charged that <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> attempted to create an artificial demand for Carbide stock after <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>'s takeover attempt failed, allegedly to allow <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> to sell its 10 percent stake at a better profit or a minimal loss. <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON>'s takeover defense, which was designed by the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law firm <LOCATION> Skadden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arps </LOCATION>, Slate, <ORGANIZATION> Meagher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flom </ORGANIZATION>, is considered possibly the first attempt to capitalize on Wall Street's insider trading scandal. The idea could signal a trend, as several other major takeover players are under investigation in the scandal. It was not clear whether <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> actually intended to mount a takeover bid for <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON>, however. Telephone calls to the company seeking comment on Monday night were not answered. <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON> has been considered by some analysts as a candidate for takeover or restructuring aimed at boosting its stock price. Cabot shares rose $ 3 to $ 37 a share Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. With some 27 million common shares outstanding, <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON> had a market value of about $ 999 million based on Monday's closing price. A <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> spokesman told the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> over the weekend that `` we have no comment whatsoever with regard to <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON>'s mean-spirited response to our company's filing. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> first disclosed its stake in <LOCATION> Cabot </LOCATION> in 1986, according to a company spokesman.
