<HEAD>Stocks Lower, Dollar Higher In Tokyo Morning Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE morning closing figures, adds
quotes. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices dipped in morning trading Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar inched up against the Japanese yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the exchange's main index, declined 114.09 points to 27,787.20 by the close of morning trading The dollar, which opened at 133.20 yen, up from 132.95 yen at Monday's close, was changing hands at 133.13 yen in late morning trading. Securities dealers said the decline in the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market primarily was due to a 33-point decline overnight in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` In very thin trading, share prices are lower across the board,'' said a dealer at a major <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> securities firm. `` This is because of unfavorable factors in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report scheduled to come out soon.'' Dealers also said they expect no major market shifts until the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report for June, scheduled for later Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
